<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-Series-Notebook,0982 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yanks offense wakes up
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JOSH DUBOW &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ The Yankees offense is performing to the nines.
	   As in nine runs a game _ the output they have produced in each
of the last three games.
	   After an offensive slumber that saw the most prolific scoring
team in baseball muster just 27 runs in the first eight games of
the playoffs, New York has managed to come up with that same total
in the last three games.
	   ``It's nice to be able to pick up the pitchers,'' said Chuck
Knoblauch, who set the tone by drawing an eight-pitch walk to lead
off the game, stealing second, and scoring on Ken Caminiti's
throwing error.
	   ``They have been carrying us the last two weeks. It's nice to
finally give them some breathing room.''
	   New York's offensive resurgence has been keyed by quick starts.
The Yankees have scored 29 of their 54 runs this postseason in the
first three innings. They had seven runs off Andy Ashby by the end
of the third in Game 2.
	   New York has outscored the opposition 15-2 in the first inning
and has scored in the first inning in 10 of its 11 games.
	   ``Scoring early means a lot to the club,'' hitting coach Chris
Chambliss said. ``It takes the pressure off and gives everybody
confidence.''
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; BERNIE'S FUTURE: Yankees general manager Brian Cashman's first
order of business this offseason will be trying to keep center
fielder Bernie Williams in New York.
	   Williams, the AL batting champion and MVP of the 1996 ALCS, has
avoided discussing his impending free agency.
	   ``We'll try to address it as soon as the season is over and try
to find out where he stands, where we stand,'' Cashman said before
Game 2 Sunday night. ``And hopefully the comfort levels will match
and we'll have a continuing, long-lasting relationship.''
	   Williams' agent, Scott Boras, has fought with Yankees owner
George Steinbrenner each winter over contracts, and the sides
didn't get anywhere last year when they discussed a multiyear deal.
	   It's unclear if Williams will give the Yankees preference in
talks once he is free to deal with any team. If Williams leaves,
New York might target Ray Lankford, who played for Joe Torre in St.
Louis.
	   ``That's why it's a juggling act,'' Cashman said. ``It's all
just part of a puzzle. And obviously, his piece is going to be a
lot bigger than everybody else's.''
	   In what the Yankees hope wasn't a sign of the future, public
address announcer Bob Sheppard skipped over Williams' name in
Saturday's lineup announcement.
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; IN A PINCH: The Padres' three pinch-hits in the eighth inning
tied a World Series record set by Oakland in 1972.
	   Ruben Rivera doubled and Carlos Hernandez singled off Mike
Stanton. After Stanton threw ball one to Chris Gomez, Joe Torre
brought in Jeff Nelson.
	   Bruce Bochy responded by sending in Mike Sweeney, who hit an RBI
single to tie the record.
	   Jim Leyritz earlier struck out that inning as San Diego also
tied the record for most pinch-hitters used in an inning.
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; TOUGH LUCK: San Diego's Wally Joyner was robbed of hits in his
first two at-bats by sterling plays in the field.
	   With two on and two out in the first, Joyner hit a shot to deep
right that Paul O'Neill caught crashing into the wall to save two
runs.
	   By the time Joyner was robbed of a single on a diving stop by
Chuck Knoblauch in the fourth, New York led 7-0.
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; VAUGHN'S REVENGE: Greg Vaughn's injured quadriceps forced him
into the designated hitter slot for San Diego in Game 2.
	   Vaughn, who did not start four games in the NLCS because of the
injury, was replaced in left field by John Vander Wal.
	   ``His quad was bothering him just a little bit yesterday,''
manager Bruce Bochy said. ``This allows us to keep him off his legs
a little bit and with the day off tomorrow, hopefully this thing
will clear up.''
	   Bochy wanted to make sure Vaughn's bat would be in the lineup,
after hitting 50 homers in the regular season and two in Game 1.
	   The two shots off David Wells were especially sweet for the
Padres, who traded Vaughn to the Yankees last July only to have it
voided by George Steinbrenner because of Vaughn's injured shoulder.
	   ``Sometimes the trade that is never made is the best one,''
Bochy said. ``That is how we feel about this. We are lucky the
trade didn't happen.''
	   For his part, Vaughn holds no ill will toward the Yankees and
says he is not trying to prove a point against them.
	   ``It's not about Greg Vaughn trying to get revenge on the
Yankees for what happened last year,'' Vaughn said. ``It's about
the San Diego Padres and New York Yankees playing in the World
Series to see who can get that ring.''
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; SHAGGING FLIES: With the series shifting to San Diego on
Tuesday, Yankees designated hitter Chili Davis has started shagging
flies and taking grounders.
	   Joe Torre said Davis could replace Tino Martinez at first base
in a double switch but would more likely see time in left if he
plays the field for the first time this season.
	   ``He has been working in the outfield and that is not out of the
realm of possibility that he is liable to play in left field,''
Torre said.
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; ODDS AND ENDS: One night after Sammy Sosa threw out the first
pitch, Roger Maris' six children did the honor. Kevin, Randy,
Richard, Roger Jr., Sandra and Susan got a standing ovation from
the crowd at the stadium where their father broke Babe Ruth's
season home run record in 1961. ... San Diego starters have an
11.17 ERA in seven World Series games. ... The Yankees have won six
consecutive World Series games, the second longest active streak.
Cincinnati has won nine straight since losing to Boston in the
sixth game of the 1975 Series. San Diego has now lost five
straight, tying the Giants for the longest active streak.
</TEXT>
