<SLUG> BC-Sports-RugbyL-New Zealand </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Halligan boosts Kiwis for Britain tour
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) _ Kiwi rugby league star Daryl
Halligan has changed his mind and decided to join New Zealand on
its tour to Britain later this month.
	   The Canterbury goalkicking ace said he was unlikely to go on the
tour after replacing injured Matthew Ridge for third test loss
against Australia on Friday.
	   But after discussing the matter with his wife, Halligan decided
to make himself available and was named Monday in the squad for the
three-test series.
	   ``We're just delighted to have him join us for the tour,'' Kiwi
coach Frank Endacott said Monday. ``I really didn't want us going
over there without a recognized goalkicker and having Daryl just
gives us that extra because we'll be up against a British side that
will have all their players available.''
	   Three rookies were named in the squad with junior Kiwis Ali
Lautiti, who made an enormous impact at the Auckland Warriors this
year, and Canberra winger Lesley Vainikolo joined by Illawarra-St
George forward Craig Smith.
	   The rest of the squad is predictable with Endacott retaining the
17 from last Friday night's test plus Nigel Vagana, who missed out
on the interchange bench.
	   Wigan's Henry Paul, who missed the tests against Australia
because of the British Super League playoffs, will join the Kiwis
after the final against Leeds.
	   Auckland Warriors prop Quentin Pongia will captain the side
after Ridge announced his international retirement.
	   ``I think it is an exciting team with a good balance of
experience and a lot of excellent young talent,'' Endacott said.
	   ``It sets us up well for the future with young guys in the
forwards like Tony Puletua who is only 19, Nathan Cayless who is
20, Ali Lautiti and Lesley Vainikolo who are just as young, as well
as Craig Smith who finally gets his chance.''
	   The Kiwis will leave Friday.
	   Squad: Richie Barnett (Sydney City), Sean Hoppe (Auckland),
Lesley Vainikolo (Canberra), Kevin Iro (St Helens), Nigel Vagana
(Auckland), Ruben Wiki (Canberra), Daryl Halligan
(Canterbury-Bankstown), Robbie Paul (Bradford), Gene Ngamu
(Auckland), Stacey Jones (Auckland), Logan Swann (Auckland),
Stephen Kearney (Auckland), Jarrod McCracken (Parramatta), Nathan
Cayless (Parramatta), Tony Iro (Adelaide), Craig Smith (St
George-Illawarra), Tony Puletua (Penrith), Ali Lautiti (Auckland),
Quentin Pongia (Auckland, captain), Joe Vagana (Auckland), Syd Eru
(Auckland), Henry Paul (Wigan).
