<SLUG> BC-Vietnam-Growth </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Source: Vietnam Central Committee sets growth target for 1999
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) _ The Communist Party Central Committee has
set Vietnam's economic growth target for 1999 at 5 percent to 6
percent, a government source said Monday.
	   The figure, which is expected to be approved by the National
Assembly at a month-long session that starts Oct. 28, was
established at a Central Committee plenum that ended Saturday.
	   The 1998 target originally was 9 percent, but the figure was
downgraded in July to between 6 percent and 7 percent as the impact
of the Asian economic crisis hit the country increasingly hard.
Government figures say growth has been 6 percent so far this year.
	   In addition, the government has said the growth target is only a
goal, not a figure that must be achieved, as was the case before
Vietnam began switching from a central command economy to a market
economy a decade ago.
	   Some economists have said the growth figures have been inflated
and the 1999 target is believed to be optimistic. Unemployment has
been rising, and growth in both exports and foreign investment has
slowed dramatically.
	   Fearing higher costs of dollar-denominated debts and needed
imports, the government has taken a cautious approach in dealing
with the regional economic crisis.
	   It has kept inflation largely in check by allowing small
periodic devaluations of the dong instead of the heavy plunges that
other countries' currencies suffered. But that also has made its
exports relatively more expensive. 	   
</TEXT>
