<SLUG> BC-Vietnam-Drug Trafficking </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two death sentences issued for Vietnam drug traffickers
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) _ A Hanoi court has sentenced two convicted
drug traffickers to death and two associates to life in prison,
local press reports said Monday.
	   All four men, who had been charged with dealing in 360 grams
(12.7 ounces) of heroin, have 15 days to appeal.
	   In July 1997, Vietnam's legislature toughened penalties on drug
trafficking: trafficking in or possessing one kilogram (2.2 pounds)
of opium or 100 grams (3.5 ounces) of heroin is punishable by death
or life imprisonment.
	   Despite the government's intensified effort to fight drugs,
abuse is on the rise and spreading to schools. Official statistics
say Vietnam has 134,000 drug addicts, with 70 percent under age 30.
	   The Labor newspaper reported Monday that drug rehabilitation
facilities in Hanoi over the past five months have provided
treatment for 756 drug addicts, including 31 government employees. 	   
</TEXT>
