<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Storms,0436 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hurricane Lester turns out to sea, Madeline churns toward coast
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Madeline was centered near latitude 21.3 north, longitude
106.5 west. Lester was centered near latitude 14.3 north, longitude
99.7 west. &QL; 
 &UR; By GREG BULL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MAZATLAN, Mexico (AP) _ Officials warned residents on Mexico's
western Pacific coast to prepare for Hurricane Madeline after the
storm changed course and headed for this resort city.
	   Hurricane Lester, which had threatened the southern Pacific
coast in Oaxaca and Guerrero states, also took a turn, heading
westward on a path that could take it out to sea. Hurricane
warnings were discontinued from Salina Cruz to Acapulco, but ships
were advised to stay in port.
	   The first to feel Madeline's wrath was expected to be prisoners
at a penal colony on the Maria Madre island, about 100 miles south
of Mazatlan. The hurricane was expected to pass over that and two
other islands.
	   Madeline, with 85 mph (135 kph) winds, was located about 35
miles (55 kilometers) south of the islands Sunday night and was
moving north at 3 mph (5 kph). The storm originally had been
heading toward landfall further south of Mazatlan.
	   A spokeswoman for the Interior Secretariat, which oversees
prisons and domestic security, said she had no information on how
many prisoners were on the island or what precautions had been
taken in advance of the storm.
	   A hurricane warning was in effect for a stretch of the Pacific
coast from Mazatlan, 530 miles (850 kilometers) northwest of Mexico
City, to an area south of Puerto Vallarta.
	   Just south of Mazatlan, authorities of neighboring Nayarit state
went house to house in coastal communities to warn people about the
hurricane and army troops prepared to aid residents, the government
news agency Notimex reported.
	   Hurricane Lester was 180 miles (290 kilometers) south of the
resort city of Acapulco, moving west near 8 mph (13 kph), according
to the National Weather Service in Miami. But it warned that a
northward deviation from its course could bring Lester, with its
105 mph (170 kph) winds closer to the coast.
	   In Acapulco, where more than 150 people died a year ago when
Hurricane Pauline swept the city, authorities evacuated 125 people
living in low-lying areas.
	   ``Even though there hasn't been any rain yet, we don't want the
hurricane to take us by surprise,'' said Melquiades Olmedo,
Acapulco civil defense director.
	   The weather service said Lester could gather strength over the
next day and cause heavy rains, flash flooding and mud slides along
the coast. 	   
</TEXT>
