w1096 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-Poverty     10-19 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Poverty </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. says Cambodia losing momentum in fight against poverty
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo PHN101 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Continuing political instability is
eroding gains made in the battle against poverty in Cambodia, the
U.N. Development Program warned Monday.
	   ``The momentum achieved in the fight against poverty _ surely
the only legitimate fight in today's Cambodia _ is being lost,''
said UNDP chief representative Paul Matthews.
	   Noting that significant progress had been made to develop
Cambodia since a 1993 election ended decades of civil war, Matthews
called on the country's bickering political parties to work
together to reduce poverty and protect the environment.
	   ``Whatever the divergence in rhetoric, the manifestos of the
main political parties all pledge to reduce poverty and to preserve
the environment,'' he told a conference observing the International
Day for the Eradication of Poverty.
	   Cambodian leader Hun Sen's ruling party and the two-party
opposition are locked in a tense stalemate over the formation of a
new government following July's disputed election.
	   Hun Sen's party won a majority of seats in parliament, but not
the two-thirds needed to form a government alone.
	   The opposition, claiming Hun Sen's victory was achieved through
fraud and intimidation, refuses to cooperate until its allegations
are thoroughly investigated.
	   Matthews said the instability was having a negative impression
on major aid donors.
	   Many donors halted aid after Hun Sen ousted Prince Norodom
Ranariddh as his co-prime minister in a violent coup d'etat last
year.
	   The political crisis that followed, along with the Southeast
Asian economic crisis, are making Cambodia's attempts to alleviate
widespread poverty more difficult, he said.
	   Cambodia ranks 140 out of 174 countries measured by the UNDP's
human development index _ a calculation including gross national
product per capita, life expectancy and literacy _ making it one of
the world's poorest countries.
	   During the poverty day observance, the UNDP released its annual
human development report for Cambodia. This year's report focused
on the plight of women in the country.
	   Cambodian women play a larger role in the work force than in any
other Southeast Asian country, but face severe wage discrimination
and are poorly represented in the higher levels of administration
and politics, the report noted.
	   Shortcomings in Cambodia's health services have had a drastic
impact on women, according to the report. The country has the
highest maternal mortality rate in the Asia-Pacific region, with
473 mothers dying for every 100,000 live births.
	   Acting Minister of Planning Soy Sem pledged at the conference to
recommend programs that will target women in Cambodia's five-year
socioeconomic development plan. 	   
</TEXT>
