<SLUG> BC-Mideast Talks, 4th Ld,0201 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Clinton holds talks past midnight, no word of West Bank deal
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITS to fix slug &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with talks ending for the night. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos WX107-108, AWYE203,206-207,405-408 &QL; 
 &UR; By BARRY SCHWEID &QC; 
 &UR; AP Diplomatic Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   QUEENSTOWN, Maryland (AP) _ President Bill Clinton made an
exceptional effort to unsnarl Middle East peace negotiations
between Israel and the Palestinians. He worked into the early
morning hours Monday on a land-for-peace deal that was stalled over
security and other key issues.
	   Still, there was no sign of a breakthrough as the president
boarded his helicopter to return to Washington close to 1:30 a.m
Monday.
	   The parties' differences over security and other key issues were
resisting American prodding at the highest levels, and Clinton was
expected to return later Monday for more talks with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
	   After seeing Arafat twice and Netanyahu once, the president had
a midnight meeting with Ariel Sharon _ at the hard-line Israeli
foreign minister's request _ which ran past 1 a.m.
 &UR; Amid reports, pickup 5th graf, 3rd Ld-Writethru
