r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-Mahathir     10-19 0299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Mahathir </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Malaysian leader to Africa: Asian way still a good strategy
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The strategies used to propel Asia to economic
prosperity are still valid despite the region's plummet into
financial crisis, Malaysia's leader told a conference on African
development Monday.
	   Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad told the Second Tokyo
International Conference on African Development that African
countries could benefit from studying East Asian economies.
	   ``Adopting the Asian approach and the Asian way towards
development is still a good strategy,'' Mahathir told the
conference, which gathered representatives from 82 countries and 40
organizations.
	   Mahathir, whose own country is facing mounting economic
problems, blamed the region's turmoil on out-of-control capitalism
rather than structural defects in the countries' economies.
	   ``Currency trading and raids in the stock market are not the
fault of Asians or their ways or their value system,'' said
Mahathir. ``Any country subject to such destructive attacks will
fail.''
	   Mahathir is on a five-day trip to Japan to meet with business
leaders and bankers _ his first trip abroad since a political
crisis erupted over his ouster and arrest of his former protege,
Anwar Ibrahim.
	   The Malaysian leader, in power for 17 years, has blamed
international currency traders and market players for the demise of
Asian economies rather than the domestic mismanagement or
corruption that others have pointed to.
	   Mahathir said that despite the region's problems, it should get
more involved in helping Africa develop.
	   ``It is timely that the Asian countries like Japan and to a
lesser extent Malaysia and others should stretch out a helping
hand,'' he told the conference.
 &UR; (jc-aptn)
</TEXT>
