	   WORLD AT 0600 GMT:
 &UR; NEW:
	   _US-CLINTON-JONES. New documents could add to president's
embarrassment.
	   _US-MICROSOFT. Antitrust trial gets under way.
	   _ASIA COMPLICATIONS. APEC summit facing some unusual risks and
opportunities.
	   _PAKISTAN-VIOLENT CITY. Another 5,000 policemen to patrol
Karachi.
 &UR; MAIN SPOT NEWS:
	   LAGOS, Nigeria _ Firefighters battle an oil-fed inferno that
swept through several villages and killed at least 250 people after
thieves apparently trying to siphon fuel from a pipeline sparked an
explosion. NIGERIA-OIL EXPLOSION. Has moved; developments will be
expedited. By Frank Aigbogun. AP Graphic NIGERIA EXPLOSION.
	   BOGOTA, Colombia _ President Andres Pastrana has pleaded for
``gestures of peace'' from leftist rebels suspected in an oil
pipeline blast that killed 45 villagers and injured 60 when it sent
flames racing through a rural hamlet. COLOMBIA-PIPELINE BLAST. Has
moved; developments will be expedited. By Jared Kotler. AP Photos
BOG101-105.
	   QUEENSTOWN, Maryland _ President Bill Clinton makes an
exceptional effort to unsnarl Middle East peace negotiations
between Israel and the Palestinians. He works into the early
morning hours Monday on a land-for-peace deal that was stalled over
security and other key issues. MIDEAST TALKS. Has moved;
developments will be expedited. By Barry Schweid. AP Photos
WX107-108; AWYE203,206-207,405-408.
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Yugoslav army tanks and other armor have
moved close to the area of a deadly attack on Serb police in
Kosovo, raising the possibility of retaliatory strikes on ethnic
Albanian guerrillas responsible for the police killings.
YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO. Has moved; developments will be expedited. By
George Jahn. AP Photos PRI103-106.
	   ALSO MOVED:
	   _US-KOSOVO _ Holbrooke stresses that NATO ready to attack
Yugoslavia.
	   _YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO-AGREEMENT _ Status of Milosevic's promises.
	   _KOSOVO-SITTING DUCKS _ Peace agreement leaves Serbian police
feeling cornered. AP Photos PRI103.
	   LONDON _ The British government has defended its arrest of
former Chilean President Gen. Augusto Pinochet, denying claims by
Chile that Britain violated the former dictator's diplomatic
immunity. BRITAIN-PINOCHET. Has moved; developments will be
expedited. By Maureen Johnson. AP Photos LON104-106.
	   SANTIAGO, Chile _ The Chilean government has dispatched a
prominent diplomat to London, hoping he can persuade British
authorities to release former dictator Gen. Augusto Pinochet from
custody. CHILE-PINOCHET. Has moved. By Eva Vergara. AP Photos
SCL101-114.
