w1127 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Taiwan-China     10-19 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-China </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taiwan affirms talks with China, but remains wary
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ANNIE HUANG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ A Taiwanese envoy's path-breaking visit to
China held out hope for improved relations between the
long-estranged rivals, but uncertainties remain and some analysts
said Monday they see few signs of lessening confrontation.
	   Amid sometimes pointed discussions, the two sides failed to
bridge wide differences that led to a three-year freeze in
relations, although they agreed to keep talking.
	   ``Such frank exchanges of opinions are something to be
affirmed,'' Sheu Ke-sheng, vice chairman of Taiwan's government
Mainland Affairs Council, said Monday after Taiwan's chief envoy,
Koo Chen-fu, wrapped up his five-day trip to China.
	   But Sheu noted at a news conference that China did not make any
adjustments to its claim that Taiwan is a part of China with no
right to sovereignty.
	   Koo argued during meetings with his Chinese counterpart, Wang
Daohan, that Taiwan is a sovereign state and will accept no other
status. Koo cited the 1945 Potsdam pact that handed the island to
the Republic of China, the official name Taiwan has adopted, from
its former colonial ruler, Japan.
	   Speaking to the Chinese leaders in Beijing as well as to a home
TV audience that has been wary of the talks, Koo said at the end of
his trip on Sunday that reunification must wait until China has
democracy. Koo said before leaving the Chinese capital that he
dared not hope that the trip would soon break the ice between
Taiwan and China, but he hoped that a thaw could eventually begin.
	   Chiang Kai-shek's Nationalists lost the mainland to Mao
Tse-tung's communist forces after a civil war in 1949, and took
refuge on the island.
	   Both sides claimed for years to be the legitimate government for
all of China, but rulers of mainland China fear Taiwan is
abandoning its old doctrine of reunifying with the motherland after
becoming a full-fledged democracy in recent years.
	   Taiwanese newspapers hailed Koo's visit as a first step to
improving ties, but they remained wary about how to proceed.
	   ``The impact of the mainland trip has yet to be assessed, but
the interactions during these five days will no doubt be an
important chapter in history,'' the China Times said in an
editorial.
	   The newspaper, one of Taiwan's two largest dailies, called for
both sides to further negotiate a plan ``that takes into
consideration both history and reality'' so they can resolve the
sovereignty dispute.
	   The rival United Daily News urged Taiwanese to watch for Chinese
President Jiang Zemin's forthcoming trip to Japan, to see whether
he would seek Japan's support to further back its claim to Taiwan.
	   Political scientist Kuo Cheng-liang, who traveled with the
Taiwanese delegation to Beijing, called the trip a setback for
Taiwan, which had hoped to coax Chinese leaders into accepting the
``new thinking'' of accepting Taiwan as its equal.
	   ``With the abortion of the new thinking,'' Kuo wrote in the
China Times, ``political dialogue has virtually broken off and the
two sides shall go back to their former diplomatic wrestling.''
	   Many Taiwanese are withholding judgment on the talks for now.
But some were antagonized by the televised comments from Chinese
officials restating China's claim over Taiwan.
	   ``Those comments really made me angry,'' said Mary Chiu, an
office worker. ``You have no choice but to deal with your neighbor.
But if he continues to be so domineering, do you still want to make
friends with him?''
 &UR; (ah-db-txw)
</TEXT>
