<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Land Suicide </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai villager who lost land hangs himself near Government House
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ A 62-year-old Thai villager who said
bureaucrats stole his land, hanged himself outside the government's
executive office building Monday, police said.
	   Choom Sakhorn, from the province of Sisaket, 430 kilometers (267
miles) northeast of Bangkok, hanged himself from a tree across the
street from Government House, where Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
and his Cabinet conduct state business, at about 3 a.m.
	   Choom had traveled to Bangkok several times during the past year
to petition the Land Department to regain his land. He said local
Land Department officials had conspired with businessmen to cheat
him out of the holding, which he valued at 370,000 baht (dlrs
9,736), police said.
	   The Land Department, part of the Interior Ministry, conducted an
internal investigation and concluded its officials had done nothing
wrong.
	   Academics, law enforcement officials and real estate consultants
have said land ownership titles are a major source of corruption
money in Thailand.
	   Several times during the past five years, tens of thousands of
farmers have protested outside Government House, chiefly over land
rights.
	   They have demanded compensation for land appropriated by the
government or businessmen, or else made worthless as a result of
development projects. 	   
</TEXT>
