u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru   10-19 0453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar lower against yen, Japanese stocks rise in afternoon
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with closing Nikkei, midafternoon dollar &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar fell sharply against the Japanese
yen Monday as worries about the American economy gained the upper
hand over those about Japan's. Tokyo stock prices rose.
	   The dollar bought 114.28 yen as of midafternoon, down 2.16 yen
from late Friday in Tokyo and also below its New York level of
115.25 yen late Friday.
	   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 286.66
points, or 2.16 percent, to finish at 13,567.20 points. On Friday,
the key index closed up 285.17 points, or 2.19 percent.
	   One major reason behind the dollar's drop was technical, dealers
said. Market players who had been waiting to sell the dollar have
finally started to do so to guard against a further fall.
	   Heightened worries about the future of the American economy were
another factor, they said.
	   The U.S. Federal Reserve's surprise move last week to cut two
key short-term interest rates was an attempt to encourage spending
and consumer confidence, but it had the effect of renewing worries
about the domestic economy.
	   Expectations the Federal Reserve may cut interest rates again
helped weigh down the dollar. Lower interest rates tend to push a
nation's currency down.
	   ``Financial market confusion in the U.S. will likely continue
for some time,'' said Shuji Takano, assistant manager of foreign
exchange at ABN Amro Bank in Tokyo. ``As long as there is
instability, there will be dollar-selling pressure.''
	   Rising Tokyo share prices also helped boost the yen and push the
dollar lower.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section rose 16.24 points, or 1.61 percent, to 1,022.92
points. The TOPIX closed up 26.57 points, or 2.71 percent, on
Friday.
	   ``It makes you think that, at last, Japan-selling is ending and
that Japan-buying is beginning,'' said Ryohei Muramatsu, foreign
exchange manager at Commerzbank in Tokyo.
	   Stocks started higher following the passage of Japanese bank
reform legislation last Friday, which will make available a pool of
public funds of up to 60 trillion yen (dlrs 524.9 billion) to
cash-strapped banks.
	   ``The market is also being helped up by the relative stability
of overseas markets,'' said Naoki Takahashi, manager at Marusan
Securities.
	   In New York Friday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 117.40
points to 8416.76.
	   The yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government
bond fell to 0.830 percent from Friday's finish of 0.865 percent,
driving its price up to 108.67 yen from 108.33 yen.
 &UR; (km-dj-yk)
</TEXT>
