<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Explosion, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two explosions at Beersheba central bus station; dozens injured
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with assailant caught and handed to police &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BEERSHEBA, Israel (AP) _ An assailant threw two hand grenades
into the central bus station in this desert town during morning
rush hour Monday, and at least 30 people were injured by the
blasts, witnesses and radio reports said.
	   One of the injured was in serious condition.
	   The assailant, apparently an Arab, was caught by passers-by who
wrestled him to the ground and handed him to police.
	   The attack coincided with a make-or-break Mideast peace summit
at Wye plantation outside Washington. A key issue on the agenda is
Israel's demand that the Palestinians do more to prevent terror
attacks in Israel. Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has
said he will not hand over West Bank land until he receives
ironclad guarantees from Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
	   Israel radio said Netanyahu was woken up by aides and briefed
about the attack.
	   The blasts went off shortly after 8 a.m. (0600 gmt) in the
central bus station of Beersheba, a town in the southern Negev
Center.
	   Israeli radio reports said at least 30 people were injured and
received treatment at Sorokka Hospital in Beersheba. Most suffered
minor injuries. Paramedics from the Magen David Adom emergency
service said at least one person was in serious condition.
	   There was no immediately claim of responsibility. Israel has
been on high alert for a possible terror attack for the past month
after the Islamic militant group Hamas said it would carry out
bombings in Israel. Hamas wants to avenge the killings of two Hamas
top fugitives by Israeli troops in September.
 &UR; kl
</TEXT>
