<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Storm </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tropical storm Babs heads towards central Philippines
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Just days after a major typhoon
killed dozens of people, tropical storm Babs crept towards the
central Philippines on Monday, picking up strength after
momentarily loosing steam, weathermen said.
	   At noon (0400 GMT), Babs, with maximum sustained winds of 75 kph
(46 mph) and gusts of up to 120 kph (75 mph), was over the Pacific
Ocean about 450 kilometers (280 miles) east southeast of Borongan
town in Eastern Samar province, said forecaster Rene Molina.
	   Molina said the storm would begin to be felt in Samar by late
Monday or early Tuesday after having stalled at sea for several
days.
	   Molina said Babs, the ninth storm to hit the country this year,
was likely to pick up speed and strength as it neared Samar. It was
moving at a speed of 11 kph (7 mph).
	   As Babs approached, disaster officials continued to look for
about 65 people still missing after Typhoon Zeb slammed the
northern Philippines last week.
	   Zeb killed at least 74 people and forced more than 415,000
others to flee their homes at the height of its onslaught. Most of
those who fled have returned to repair their damaged homes.
	   The typhoon destroyed an estimated 1.5 billion pesos (dlrs 35
million) worth of property and crops in 1,087 northern villages in
the country's tobacco- and rice-growing region, officials said.
	   After hitting the Philippines, Zeb moved on to skirt Taiwan,
where 18 died, before cutting a swath across Japan. At least 12
people were killed in Japan. 	   
</TEXT>
