<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Pakistan-Australia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Second Test heading toward a draw
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RIZWAN ALI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) _ Australia was likely to keep its 1-0
lead in the three-match series in tact against Pakistan as the
second Test appeared to be heading toward a draw on Monday, the
fifth and final day.
	   At lunch, Australia was 93 for two, an overall lead of 112 runs
with eight second innings wickets in hand. The visitors ended their
first innings declaring at 599 for four declared.
	   Pakistan replied with a strong 580 for nine declared in its
first innings.
	   First innings triple century-maker Mark Taylor was unbeaten on
42 while Mark Waugh was with him on 14 at lunch.
	   Spectators were watching to see whether Taylor would break
England's Graham Gooch record for the highest number of runs in one
Test. Gooch scored 333 and 123 in a Lord's Test against India in
1990 for an accumulated run total of 456 runs.
	   Taylor, who scored unbeaten 334 in the first innings needs
another 81 runs in the remaining two sessions to surpass Gooch's
record.
	   Taylor has thus far made 376 in two innings and is just four shy
of Greg Chappell's 380-run mark. Chappell scored (247 not out) and
133 in his two innings against New Zealand at Wellington in 1973-74
season and is second behind Gooch.
	   Leg-spinner Mushtaq Ahmed got both the wickets in the first
session after Australia resumed at 21 for no loss. The leg-spinner
bowled 14 overs in the first session. He trapped Michael Slater leg
before for 21 and then first innings centurion Justin Langer (14)
was neatly caught by Yousuf Youhanna at forward short leg.
 &UR; (str/kg)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Cricket-Pakistan-Australia; CT:s; 
(REG:MEST;)
