w1208 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-China-MarketRegulatio     10-19 0369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Market Regulation </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China approves new mandate for securities market regulator
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SHANGHAI, China (AP) _ China's government has approved a
sweeping new mandate for its securities market regulator in a
long-awaited move aimed at unifying oversight functions in its
fledgling securities industry, state media reported Monday.
	   The new arrangement gives the China Securities Regulatory
Commission full regulatory authority over both China's securities
and futures, effectively ending a period in which the markets and
brokerage and investment houses were regulated by several different
government entities.
	   The expanded oversight functions are part of efforts to end
widespread market abuses such as price manipulation and insider
trading that have long existed due to the murky regulatory
environment, officials at the CSRC said Monday.
	   Under the new regime, the CSRC will be charged with formulating
all new securities market laws and policies, and with approving and
regulating all issuance and trading of stocks, convertible bonds,
investment funds and futures contracts.
	   The new mandate also formally puts the CSRC in charge of the top
personnel at the country's two stock exchanges, futures exchanges
and local market regulatory offices.
	   The body also becomes responsible for approving the
qualifications of all senior personnel at mainland-based securities
and futures brokerages, the reports said.
	   The CSRC has also won authority for regulating the overseas
operations of all domestic stock and futures brokerages and the
domestic operations of all foreign brokerages in China.
	   The mandate makes the CSRC China's only body that can approve
institutions to release market statistics and information, a move
aimed at cracking down on information providers that release
inaccurate information to move markets in their favor.
	   Since 1991, the number of listed companies in China has soared
to more than 800 from just 10, while total market capitalization
has leaped to some dlrs 250 billion from just dlrs 145 million,
giving China one of largest markets in Asia, even though China's
exchanges in Shanghai and Shenzhen remain largely closed to foreign
funds.	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-China-Market Regulation; CT:f; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
