<HEADER>
w1210 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKorea-KiaAuction 1stLd-Writethru   10-19 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Kia Auction, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hyundai selected as successful bidder for bankrupt Kia Motors
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with statements by creditor banks and Hyundai
president, grafs 8-10; minor editing throughout &QL; 
 &UR; By KYONG-HWA SEOK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Outbidding Ford Motor Co. and two
domestic competitors, Hyundai Motor Co. was tentatively selected
Monday as the winner in an auction to take over bankrupt Kia Motors
Corp.
	   The selection of Hyundai, South Korea's No. 1 car maker,
however, is subject to approval by creditor banks, which had made
no secret of their hope that cash-rich Ford would win the auction.
	   Hyundai's bid beat offers by the U.S. auto giant and South
Korea's Daewoo Motors Co. and Samsung Motors Inc., Kia officials
said.
	   Kia's collapse last year was widely believed to have triggered
South Korea's economic crisis, forcing the country to call in the
International Monetary Fund for rescue measures.
	   The government had backed Ford in the hope it would pump much
needed hard currency into the country and boost foreign investor
confidence in its economy.
	   South Korean media widely reported even before Monday's
announcement that creditor banks would reject selection of a local
company to take over Kia.
	   But Kia officials said Ford was disqualified because it offered
to buy the stock of Kia's commercial vehicle arm, Asia Motors, at a
price lower than its face value of 5,000 won (dlrs 3.78).
	   The state-run Korea Development Bank, representing about 50
creditor banks, said it would take about a week to decide whether
to accept Hyundai's bid.
	   Meanwhile, Hyundai president Chung Mong-kyu told a news
conference his company would seek investments from Ford and other
foreign and domestic automakers in its takeover bid.
	   Chung said Hyundai demanded that creditors write off 7.3
trillion won (dlrs 5.5 billion) of Kia's debt of dlrs 8.4 billion.
Hyundai already owes its own creditors 7.81 trillion won (dlrs 5.58
billion), compared with assets of 9.5 trillion won (dlrs 6.79
billion).
	   Kia officials said the selection of Hyundai was made by two
neutral, outside companies _ Anderson Consulting Co. of the United
States and Banque Nationale de Paris of France.
	   Kia officials said Hyundai submitted the best combination of
requested debt reductions and stock price bids for Kia and Asia
Motors.
	   Without giving any reasons, Kia officials said they decided not
to disclose details of the auction, including debt write-offs. The
auction was the third since August.
	   ``Now, it's up to creditor banks whether to award the bidding to
Hyundai or Ford,'' Lee Jong-dae, Kia's chief planning official,
said.
	   The national Yonhap news agency, quoting unidentified sources,
said creditor banks have reservations about the amount of debt
write-off demanded by Hyundai.
	   In two previous failed auctions, creditor banks offered to write
off dlrs 2.1 billion of Kia dlrs 8.4 billion debt. But the
potential buyers all demanded further debt reduction.
	   ``It's no secret that creditors want Ford to take over Kia,''
said Ji Seung-chul, an analyst at LG Securities Co. ``Creditors
want an early debt payment, which makes Ford the best contender.''	   
</TEXT>
