w1216 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Afghanistan-Iran-UN     10-19 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Afghanistan-Iran-UN,0463 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iran standoff with Taliban religious militia defused
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By KATHY GANNON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ After more than a week of diplomacy
that took him to the headquarters of Afghanistan's Taliban
religious militia, the United Nations special envoy said Monday
that the danger of a military confrontation between Iran and the
Taliban army had past.
	   ``Inshallah (God willing) that is behind us,'' Lakhdar Brahimi
told a news conference in the federal capital on the eve of his
departure for Iran.
	   His meetings with the Taliban resulted in the release of 26
Iranian prisoners, an inquiry into the killings in August of eight
Iranian diplomats and an Iranian journalist in northern Afghanistan
as well as a promise by the Taliban to hold face-to-face talks with
Iran.
	   The stand off between Iran and the Taliban resulted in the
deployment of more than 200,000 Iranian soldiers to their eastern
border with Afghanistan and generated fear of an all out war
between the hostile neighbors.
	   Of his visit to Pakistan and Afghanistan, Brahimi said ``they
realized that the situation has been extremely dangerous ... and
(now) they realize the need to move from this defused situation to
a real and genuine peace in Afghanistan.''
	   Now U.N. officials want to begin negotiations with the Taliban
for the return of its international staff to their country.
	   An estimated 50 foreign U.N. workers were pulled out of
Afghanistan on Aug. 21 after an Italian U.N. worker was shot and
killed in Kabul in apparent retaliation for the U.S. missile attack
on suspected terrorist camps in eastern Afghanistan.
	   ``We want to make sure our staff is safe to go back,'' said
Sarah Russell, a U.N. spokeswoman in Pakistan.
	   Currently the United Nations and the Taliban are holding
negotiations in Pakistan to try to get security guarantees and
assurances that ``there are mechanisms in place for investigating,
finding and conducting a fair trial,'' said Russell.
	   The United Nations also wants equal access to women and girls,
adequate health care for women and a guarantee that its
international Muslim women staff will be allowed to work in
Afghanistan
	   But it's likely that security guarantees alone will be enough to
get the United Nations back into Afghanistan.
	   ``We feel it is important to have an international presence
there ... we have to be there to have a dialogue,'' said Russell.
``Our Afghan staff need the support of the international staff.''
	   The Taliban rule 90 percent of Afghanistan, while their
opponents the remaining 10 percent.
	   But the fighting rages and Brahimi said the key to peace is
``genuine representation of the people of Afghanistan in a
political process.'' 	   
</TEXT>
