w1222 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 1stLd-Writethru   10-19 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Serb military force moves out of its barracks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS to UPDATE with two Serb journalists reported missing &QL; 
 &UR; By GEORGE JAHN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Serb army tanks and other military
vehicles were seen rumbling toward the site of an attack on Serb
police, leading to fears of a retaliatory strike against ethnic
Albanians in the southern province of Kosovo.
	   In Belgrade, the state-run Tanjug news agency reported Monday
that two of its journalists _ reporter Nebojsa Radosevic and
photographer Vladimir Dobricic _ went missing en route to the scene
of the attack and may have been kidnapped by ethnic Albanian
guerrillas.
	   The battle unit moved out of its barracks Sunday in the
provincial capital Pristina and headed west down the main highway
through the Komorane police checkpoint, Western observers said
speaking on condition of anonymity.
	   The tanks' ultimate destination was not known but the observers
speculated they were moved in response to recent attacks on police
by the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army.
	   NATO has threatened airstrikes unless Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic keeps his promise to reduce the number of army
troops and Serb police in Kosovo to the levels they were at before
he launched a crackdown in February. So far, nobody has specified
exactly what those levels were.
	   Hundreds of people have been killed in Milosevic's crackdown _
most of them ethnic Albanian civilians _ and hundreds of thousands
more have fled their homes to escape the violence.
	   Ninety percent of Kosovo's 2 million inhabitants are ethnic
Albanians, and most want independence from Serbia, Yugoslavia's
dominant republic.
	   Three Serb policemen died over the weekend and two others were
badly wounded by a grenade attack on a police outpost in Orlate, 30
kilometers (20 miles) southwest of Pristina.
	   The Serb-run Kosovo Media Center reported a dozen other attacks
around the province, including one on the Komorane police
checkpoint. There was no word on casualties.
	   In Belgrade, Tanjug said the two Serb journalists left Pristina
by car Sunday to check out the reported attack on the police but
never reached their destination and never returned to the Kosovo
capital.
	   A Serb reporter from Radio Pristina and his driver disappeared
in August and are believed to have been kidnapped by the KLA.
	   Meanwhile, an advance team for the 2,000-strong monitoring force
from the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
arrived Sunday in Pristina.
	   ``We hope that the overall presence of the OSCE can act in a
stabilizing fashion and hopefully we'll resolve many of the
issues,'' said John Sandrock, the American heading the Vienna-based
OSCE's mission support section. He said the OSCE mission had a
one-year mandate, which could be extended.
	   Serb officials blamed the stepped up violence on the KLA.
	   But Hydajet Hyseni, spokesman for the United Democratic
Movement, which is openly supportive of the KLA, accused the police
of attacking the ``innocent Albanian population,'' and said the KLA
only shot back in self-defense.
	   The United States and NATO have reported significant pullbacks
by Yugoslav forces in recent days but say numbers still exceed the
level required by the agreement reached last week between Milosevic
and U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke.
	   NATO has extended a deadline for compliance until Oct. 27.
	   rr/kk
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
