<HEADER>
w1224 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-Hanson-Tour     10-19 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Hanson-Tourism </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hanson's defeat will be good for tourism, industry leader says
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Right-wing populist politician Pauline
Hanson had damaged Australia's reputation as one of the world's
best tourist destinations, but her defeat in elections Oct. 3 was
making marketing of the nation easier, an industry leader said
Monday.
	   ``There is absolutely no doubt in our view that the policies of
One Nation and Pauline Hanson caused considerable damage to our
image worldwide, particularly throughout Asia ... but also in
Europe,'' said John Morse, managing director of the Tourism Council
of Australia.
	   ``What was under threat was the notion that Australia is a
friendly and welcoming country. The One Nation defeat at the
election really sent a very strong message to the world and we can
now move ahead with confidence ... (in) our promotion of Australia
as a friendly destination, as a welcoming destination.''
	   Hanson's One Nation attracted about 9 percent of the vote
nationally in the election. Hanson lost her seat in Parliament, and
only one One Nation candidate was elected.
	   Hanson's words were widely reported around the world, and
particularly in Asia, after she made a speech to Parliament in 1996
claiming Australia was being ``swamped'' by Asians and criticizing
Australia's Aborigines.
	   Opponents feared she would win substantial power in the
election, after One Nation collected about 23 percent of the vote
in a Queensland state election in June.
	   The conservative coalition of Prime Minister John Howard was
re-elected in the national poll, with a reduced majority.
	   Morse launched a new campaign Monday that he said was designed
to entice Asian tourists focusing on the ``emotional and spiritual
benefits'' of vacationing in Australia.
	   Morse said the campaign was the result of extensive research
conducted in Malaysia, Taiwan, China, Singapore and Hong Kong.
	   The Asian economic crisis has hurt tourism, with the number of
Asian tourists visiting Australia declining by 25 percent in the
year to June 30, 1998, he said.
	   ``You have to remember that that is up against a background of
five years of what can only be described as phenomenal growth. ...
Our view is if something dramatic happens, unless there is a global
recession or other factors which we're not aware of, next year
we'll start to see a return to growth again,'' Morse said.	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Australia-Hanson-Tourism; CT:i; 
