<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 10/19/1998 04:26:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1227 &Cx1f; wstm-
b i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Nigeria-OilExplosion 3rdLd-Writethru   10-19 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Oil Explosion, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: At least 420 killed in Nigerian pipeline fire
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With AP Graphic NIGERIA EXPLOSION.
 &UR; Eds: COMBINES previous with minor editing. &QL; 
 &UR; By FRANK AIGBOGUN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Firefighters were battling a gasoline-fed
inferno that swept through several villages and reportedly killed
more than 422 people after thieves apparently trying to siphon fuel
from a pipeline sparked an explosion.
	   The fire, which began late Saturday, was still blazing Sunday
night. It was unclear, however, if it continued to burn into Monday
morning. While initial reports said the pipeline was carrying oil,
Monday newspaper reports said it was refined gasoline.
	   An official death toll was not available, but the Lagos-based
Guardian newspaper reported Monday morning that its reporters had
counted 400 bodies at the scene near the town of Jesse, about 300
kilometers (180 miles) southeast of Lagos. The newspaper said it
had confirmed at least 22 other people had died in area hospitals.
	   Other unconfirmed newspaper reports put the death toll at more
than 500 people.
	   Among the dead were vandals _ including children _ whose corpses
were found still clutching plastic cups, funnels and jerry cans
intended to collect fuel from the pipeline. Many other victims were
farmers and villagers sleeping in their homes.
	   ``I cannot believe what I have seen. Corpses, corpses,''
Emmanuel Akhihiero, an official with the government oil company,
said in a telephone interview.
	   There were 230 bodies in one mound of corpses, journalists said.
	   Military commander Walter Feghabo ordered a mass burial for
bodies charred beyond recognition.
	   Feghabo said that more than 120 firefighters still were trying
late Sunday to contain the flames in Jesse and the nearby villages
of Mossogar and Oghara.
	   ``I just cannot believe this,'' Feghabo said by telephone after
surveying one pile of corpses.
	   The above-ground pipeline links an oil refinery in the
southeastern city of Warri, 350 kilometers (210 miles) southeast of
the commercial capital of Lagos, with the northern city of Kaduna,
nearly 600 kilometers (380 miles) away.
	   It exploded when thieves sabotaged the line hoping to siphon off
the liquid, an official for Nigeria's state petroleum corporation
said on condition of anonymity.
	   The official said authorities believed the vandals' tools used
to break the pipe open had caused a spark, setting the pipeline on
fire. Witnesses said they heard a load roar and saw oily flames
spread quickly as the slicks spread.
	   Vandals and protesters often sabotage petroleum pipelines in
Nigeria as a way of demanding greater financial assistance from the
government and multinational oil companies and to collect the
valuable fuel.
	   Despite Nigeria's enormous oil wealth, years of government
misrule and corruption have resulted in almost perpetual fuel
shortages that result in skyrocketing black-market prices and long
lines at the gas pumps.
	   In other parts of southeastern Nigeria, ethnic Ijaw youths have
attacked Western oil installations in recent weeks, demanding
schools, better roads and political representation. The weekend
fire, though, was not believed to be related to those incidents.
	   (fa-tjs)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Nigeria-Oil Explosion, 3rd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
