<SLUG> BC-Afghanistan-Fighting,0223 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taliban fighter planes pound opposition troops in fresh fighting
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Afghanistan's opposition alliance
repulsed an attack by the hard-line Taliban Islamic militia in
northern Afghanistan's Baghlan province, an opposition spokesman
said.
	   ``Fighter planes of the Taliban bombed our positions several
times in Baghlan province and launched a major offensive on the
ground, but our fighters repulsed the attack,'' an opposition
spokesman who identified himself only as Arif told The Associated
Press.
	   There was no immediate comment from the Taliban.
	   Arif said the Taliban fighters attacked the strategic Andarb
district of Baghlan province to push towards the Khawak pass, but
opposition fighters repulsed their offensive.
	   The area is about 110 kilometers (65 miles) from the capital
Kabul.
	   Fighting raged in the area, but there were no immediate casualty
figures.
	   On Sunday several rockets pounded Kabul killing at least three
people and wounding several more.
	   The opposition forces loyal to Ahmed Shah Massood's
Jamiat-e-Islami are trying to regain some of the lost ground.
	   Massood was the defense minister in the ousted government of
president Burhanuddin Rabbani.
	   The Taliban rule 90 percent of Afghanistan and the opposition 10
percent. 	   
</TEXT>
