<SLUG> BC-Israel-Explosion, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two explosions at Beersheba central bus station; dozens injured
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with hospital officials saying 51 injured, Hamas
reaction, quote from Netanyahu's spokesman; adds byline &QL; 
 &UR; By LAURIE COPANS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEERSHEBA, Israel (AP) _ A Palestinian threw two hand grenades
at passengers waiting in a crowded bus station during Monday
morning rush hour, and at least 51 people were injured, including
many soldiers. Two victims were in serious condition.
	   The assailant was wrestled to the ground by passers-by.
	   The attack came at a critical time in a make-or-break Mideast
peace summit at Wye plantation outside Washington. A spokesman for
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said the blasts strengthened
Israel's determination to stick to demands that the Palestinians do
more to prevent terror attacks.
	   Sheik Ahmed Yassin, founder of the Islamic militant group Hamas,
said that ``what happened this morning is part of our continued
resistance to the occupation of our land,'' but stopped short of
directly claiming responsibility for the attack.
	   Hamas has threatened to carry out terror attacks in Israel to
avenge the killing of two fugitives by Israeli troops last month.
	   The explosions went off shortly after 8 a.m. (0600 gmt) in the
central bus station of Beersheba, a town in the southern Negev
Desert.
	   Witnesses said the assailant, who came from the West Bank town
of Dahariya near Hebron, carried hand grenades in a bag.
	   He threw the grenades at a crowded bus stop where passengers
were waiting, among them many soldiers. Israel radio quoted police
as saying the suspect wanted to harm soldiers.
	   The radio said one grenade hit a bus full of passengers, but
exploded some distance away.
	   After the blasts, army-issue olive duffel bags and clothes were
seen strewn on the pavement near a glass-covered bus stop. A
soldier's polished black boots, with the socks stuffed inside, were
left behind on a traffic island.
	   Officials at Sorokka Hospital in Beersheba said 51 people were
injured, including two who were in serious condition. Most suffered
minor injuries.
	   At the Mideast summit, the key issue is Israel's demand that the
Palestinians do more to prevent terror attacks in Israel. Netanyahu
has said he will not hand over West Bank land until he receives
ironclad guarantees from Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
	   Netanyahu spokesman Aviv Bushinsky quoted the prime minister as
saying that ``the attack strengthens the Israeli position in the
negotiations with the Palestinians.''
	   Dahariya, the reported hometown of the assailant, is in a part
of the West Bank where Israel retains full security control, while
Palestinian police deal with maintaining order.
	   Israeli hardliners demanded that Netanyahu break off the
negotiations at Wye plantation, but Bushinsky said Israel would not
leave prematurely.
	   The Palestinians' security chief in the West Bank, Col. Jibril
Rajoub, said terror attacks also harmed the Palestinians because
they made it more difficult to reach a peace agreement.
	   ``Both sides must move to implement the agreement,'' Rajoub told
The Associated Press. ``Israel must understand that security comes
through peace.''
	   On Sunday evening, shots were fired at a vanload of Palestinian
laborers and three passengers were wounded. The driver of the van
said Israeli troops opened fire after the vehicle skirted a West
Bank roadblock. The army said soldiers were not involved.
 &UR; str-kl
</TEXT>
