<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Northern Ireland </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Blair will try to break deadlock on decommissioning of weapons
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Prime Minister Tony Blair will try to get the
Northern Ireland peace process back on schedule when he holds
separate meetings Monday with Protestant and Catholic leaders about
the decommissioning of weapons.
	   Blair has summoned David Trimble, leader of the Ulster Unionist
Party, and Sinn Fein's Martin McGuinness to his Downing Street
office.
	   ``Obviously the prime minister will be pressing the
decommissioning issue and seeking to crack it,'' said Blair's
spokesman, speaking with customary anonymity.
	   McGuiness is expected at 11:15 p.m. (1015 GMT) and Trimble is to
meet with Blair at 5 p.m. (1600 GMT), the spokesman said.
	   Blair hopes to take advantage of renewed optimism following the
award Friday of the Nobel Peace Prize to Trimble and John Hume,
Catholic leader of the moderate Social Democratic and Labor Party.
Blair's spokesman said the Nobel recognition could ``act as a
spur'' to break the deadlock.
	   A Northern Ireland administration of Protestants and Catholics
is supposed to hold an inaugural summit with the Irish Republic's
government by Oct. 31, one of the few specific deadlines within
April's historic peace accord.
	   But the potential 12-member administration has yet to be
appointed because two key politicians _ Trimble and Sinn Fein party
leader Gerry Adams _ can't agree whether the Irish Republican Army
must start disarming first.
	   The agreement says only that disarmament should happen by May
2000. But Trimble, chief representative of the north's British
Protestant majority, insists the IRA must demonstrate it has
renounced violence before Adams' IRA-allied party will be eligible
to participate in the new government.
	   The IRA is sticking to a July 1997 cease-fire but insists it
won't disarm, and Sinn Fein argues it shouldn't be responsible for
what the IRA does. But Sinn Fein has assigned McGuinness to work
with the official commission on surrendering weapons.
	   The Ulster Volunteer Force and the other major outlawed
pro-British group, the Ulster Defense Association, have observed a
truce since 1994 but are similarly determined to retain their less
elaborate arsenal.
	   Trimble, who is under pressure from his party to force the
decommissioning issue, has cited the Nobel prize as an added
incentive for the IRA to start disarming now.
	   ``I hope it's not premature in the sense that I hope the
republican movement will not let down everyone in Northern Ireland
who wants to see progress,'' Trimble said during a British
Broadcasting Corp. interview on Sunday.
	   But while Trimble contends that decommissioning should already
be under way, he downplayed the importance of the Oct. 31 deadline
for setting up the executive body.
	   Instead, he talked about meeting the target date of February
when Britain is due to transfer powers to the new Northern Ireland
government.
	   But Sinn Fein said McGuinness would impress on Blair the
``imperative'' of getting the executive body established by the end
of the month.
	   Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern on Sunday urged all the
parties to ``adopt a generous and forthcoming approach'' on the
weapons front and said it would be ``perverse'' if the issue was
allowed to destroy the peace process.
	   (mb-ms)
</TEXT>
