<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Georgia-Revolt </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
200 troops revolt, block roads in western Georgia
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MISHA DZHINDZHIKHASHVILI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TBILISI, Georgia (AP) _ More than 200 Georgian soldiers revolted
Monday, blocking roads in a western region with stolen tanks,
trucks and machine guns in support of the country's late
ex-president, officials said.
	   President Eduard Shevardnadze demanded that the mutinous
soldiers lay down their weapons and return to their barracks, and
threatened to use force if they continued with the revolt.
	   ``The (government) powers are controlling the situation,''
Shevardnadze said on state television.
	   Shevardnadze, who has survived assassination attempts and a
several rebellions, put Georgian troops to combat readiness, said
presidential spokesman Vakhtang Abashidze.
	   Russian television reported that by midday Monday the soldiers
had removed the tanks and stopped blockading the roads. But it was
not clear whether they had agreed to end the rebellion.
	   The revolt began when soldiers from a tank brigade in the
western town of Senaki took over their garrison and stole 10 tanks,
two armored personnel carriers, and more than 50 machine guns, said
Abashidze.
	   Some of the soldiers then blocked two roads leading to the port
city of Poti with seven of the tanks, Abashidze said.
	   The rebel soldiers were negotiating with government officials,
television reports said. Earlier, the soldiers shot at the car of a
government official coming to talk to them, but no one was wounded,
the Interfax news agency said.
	   Georgian Defense Minister Maj. Gen. David Tevzadze and the
Minister of State Security, Lt. Gen. Dzhemal Gakhokidze, were both
sent to the scene.
	   The mutiny was being led by Akakiyev Eliyava, a military
commander who is also a supporter of the late president Zviad
Gamsakhurdia, Abashidze said.
	   Gamsakhurdia, Georgia's leader when it became independent in
1991, was ousted in early 1992 and fought a short war in a bid to
return to power. He died in mysterious circumstances in 1994.
	   His followers remain bitterly opposed to Shevardnadze, and the
current president blames Gamsakhurdia's supporters for the Feb. 9
attack on his motorcade that left two of the president's bodyguards
dead. At least eight suspects have been arrested.
	   (str/nw/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
