<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar lower against yen, Japanese stocks rise
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with late afternoon dollar, bonds, new comments, other
details. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar continued its plunge against the
Japanese yen Monday on worries about instability on American
financial markets. Tokyo stock prices rose sharply.
	   The dollar cost 114.72 yen in late afternoon, down 1.72 yen from
late Friday in Tokyo and also below its New York level of 115.25
yen late Friday. It now has lost a total of 5.00 yen in three
sessions in Tokyo.
	   In Monday's Tokyo trading, the dollar ranged between 113.81 yen
and 115.90 yen.
	   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 286.66
points, or 2.16 percent, closing at 13,567.20. On Friday, the key
index had climbed 285.17 points, or 2.19 percent.
	   One major reason behind the dollar's drop was technical, dealers
said. Market players who had been waiting to sell the dollar have
finally started to do so to guard against a further fall.
	   Heightened worries about the future of the American economy were
another factor, they said.
	   The U.S. Federal Reserve's surprise move last week to cut two
key short-term interest rates was an attempt to encourage spending
and consumer confidence, but it had the effect of renewing worries
about the American economy.
	   Expectations that the Fed may cut interest rates again helped
weigh down the dollar. Lower interest rates tend to push a nation's
currency down.
	   ``Financial market confusion in the U.S. will likely continue
for some time,'' said Shuji Takano, assistant manager of foreign
exchange at ABN Amro Bank in Tokyo. ``As long as there is
instability, there will be dollar-selling pressure.''
	   Rising Tokyo share prices also helped boost the yen and push the
dollar lower.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section rose 16.24 points, or 1.61 percent, to 1,022.92. It
had gained 26.57 points, or 2.71 percent, on Friday.
	   ``It makes you think that, at last, Japan-selling is ending and
that Japan-buying is beginning,'' said Ryohei Muramatsu, foreign
exchange manager at Commerzbank in Tokyo.
	   Stocks started higher following the passage of Japanese bank
reform legislation last Friday, which will make available a pool of
public funds of up to 60 trillion yen (dlrs 524.9 billion) to
cash-strapped banks.
	   ``The passage of the recapitalization bill has helped to ease
worries about banks,'' said Masaru Arai, general manager at Ryoko
Securities.
	   Volume on the first section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange totaled
about 470 million shares, little changed from 468.99 million
Friday. Advances exceeded declines 804 to 323, while 156 issues
were unchanged.
	   ``The market is also being helped up by the relative stability
of overseas markets,'' said Naoki Takahashi, manager at Marusan
Securities.
	   In New York Friday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 117.40
points to 8,416.76.
	   The yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government
bond fell to 0.815 percent from Friday's finish of 0.865 percent,
driving its price up to 108.82 yen from 108.33 yen.
 &UR; (km-dj-yk)	   
</TEXT>
