<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Syria,0235 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkey says military action against Syria possible if diplomacy
</HEADLINE>
fails &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ While officials from Turkey and Syria
prepared to meet Monday to ease tensions, Turkish officials
indicated that it could still take military action against Syria if
it failed to satisfy demands to clamp down on Kurdish rebels.
	   ``Where diplomacy ends whatever is necessary must be done,''
Defense Minister Ismet Sezgin told TRT television in an interview
aired late Sunday.
	   High-ranking security officials were scheduled to meet at a
secret location to address Turkey's concerns that Syria is
sheltering rebels responsible for cross-border attacks.
	   Turkish officials said they would require proof that Syria was
closing down alleged Kurdish rebel camps in the Syrian-controlled
Bekaa Valley in Lebanon. Turkey also accuses Syria of sheltering
Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan.
	   Reports suggested talks would take place at a border checkpoint
inside Turkey.
	   Relations between the two neighbors deteriorated sharply in the
past few weeks after Turkey suggested it might take military action
against Syria. The threat raised fears of a regional war.
	   ``Syria has made terrorism a vehicle for its foreign policy,''
Sezgin said. ``We are demanding that Syria stop giving support to
terrorism, stop providing logistic assistance, and just end their
support.'' 	   
</TEXT>
