<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 10/19/1998 04:43:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1247 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 2ndLd-Writethru   10-19 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Serb military force moves out of its barracks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS to UPDATE with U.N. relief agency canceling convoys,
tanks reported near refugee colony; no pickup &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By GEORGE JAHN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Reacting to an upsurge in violence
in Kosovo, the U.N. refugee agency canceled two relief convoys
Monday and sent a team to investigate reports of tanks appearing
near a camp of ethnic Albanian refugees.
	   The convoys, organized by the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees, were supposed to have gone to a village near the western
Kosovo town of Klina and to Streoc, south of the province's second
largest city, Pec.
	   Traveling there would require the convoys to pass through the
Serb police checkpoint at Komorane, near the scene of weekend
attacks against Serbian forces, UNHCR spokeswoman Laura Boldrini
said.
	   The U.N. agency also sent a team to Kisna Reka, where 3,000
refugees live in a makeshift camp in the mountains, to check
reports that Serbian tanks advanced on the area last night,
Boldrini said.
	   She said the UNHCR had reports of widespread shelling during the
night, but added those reports were unconfirmed.
	   Separately, police reported that two journalists from the
government's Tanjug news agency went missing Sunday in the Magura
area, southwest of Pristina. Two others from Radio Pristina, a
journalist and his driver, have been missing since August.
	   The reports of military activity near the refugee colony
appeared connected to the movement of Yugoslav army tanks and other
armor close to the area of a deadly attack Saturday on Serb police.
	   Three Serb policemen died Saturday and two others were badly
wounded by a grenade at a police outpost in the town of Orlate, 30
kilometers (20 miles) southwest of the capital Pristina.
	   The Serb-run Kosovo Media Center in Pristina reported a dozen
other attacks around Kosovo. There was no word of casualties. Serb
officials blamed the stepped up violence on the ethnic Albanian
Kosovo Liberation Army. But KLA supporters said the guerrillas were
shooting back in self defense.
	   Western observers said the armored battle group moved out of its
base in the provincial capital of Pristina on Sunday and headed
westward down a main highway through the Komorane checkpoint about
20 miles (30 kms) to the west.
	   Its ultimate destination was not known, but the observers
speculated the military unit was moved in response to the KLA
attacks.
	   The troop movements come despite the continued threat of NATO
airstrikes. Fearing a NATO attack, Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic agreed last week to withdraw his forces from Kosovo. The
alliance has given him until Oct. 27 to comply.
	   It was not clear how many troops had been moved out of Pristina
on Sunday. But because the force is normally stationed in the
capital, it would not have to withdraw from the province under the
pullback plan.
	   The plan, negotiated by U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke, seeks to
end the bloodshed in Kosovo, a predominantly ethnic Albanian
province of Serbia. Serb-led Yugoslav launched a crackdown against
ethnic Albanian militants in the province in February following
attacks on police and soldiers.
	   Hundreds of people have been killed in Milosevic's crackdown _
most of them ethnic Albanian civilians _ and hundreds of thousands
more have fled their homes to escape the violence.
	   Ninety percent of Kosovo's 2 million inhabitants are ethnic
Albanians, and most want independence from Serbia, Yugoslavia's
dominant republic.
	   Amid the threat of new conflict, more members of an advance team
of an expected 2,000 unarmed international monitors arrived Sunday
in Kosovo.
	   The team was sent by the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, which is responsible for verifying that
Milosevic sticks to the agreement.
	   Principal among the demands is that he decrease the number of
troops and police to levels before the February crackdown. So far,
nobody has specified exactly what those levels are.
	   The United States and NATO have reported significant pullbacks
by Yugoslav forces in recent days but say numbers still exceed the
level required by the Belgrade agreement.
	   NATO plans for air attacks on Yugoslavia remain on hold after
the North Atlantic Council, NATO's top policymaking body, extended
the deadline for compliance from last Saturday to Oct. 27.
	   Asked if his current mission would have an effect on the rising
number of attacks, John Sandrock, the American heading the
Vienna-based OSCE's mission support section, said: ``We hope that
the overall presence of the OSCE can act in a stabilizing fashion
and hopefully we'll resolve many of the issues.''
	   He said the OSCE mission had a one-year mandate, which could be
extended.
	   (gj/tsc/reid)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 2nd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
