w1789 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Algeria     10-19 0338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Algeria </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report president's top adviser resigns amid controversy
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) _ Algerian President Liamine Zeroual's top
adviser, under attack for months by some of the nation's leading
newspapers, has resigned, the president's office announced Monday.
	   The resignation caps nearly six months of controversy
surrounding Gen. Mohamed Betchine that some observers interpret as
the reflection of a power struggle within the military
establishment -- the real source of power in this North African
nation preparing for early presidential elections.
	   Betchine's resignation came a day after Justice Minister Mohamed
Adami, also caught up in controversy, announced his resignation.
	   Zeroual, a retired general, last month announced he would cut
short his five-year presidential term, holding early elections
before the end of February. His term was to end in the year 2000.
	   Zeroual unflinchingly defended Betchine, a personal friend.
	   Betchine, presidential adviser since April 1994, has been
criticized by the press on a variety of counts, including alleged
abuse of power connected to commercial interests and and alleged
torture during riots in October 1988, when he headed the country's
intelligence apparatus.
	   Speaking out against charges for the first time since the
controversy surrounding him erupted last June, Betchine defended
himself in an interview last week in the newspaper ``Demain
l'Algerie.''
	   ``My enemies think they are pushing me to react .... They are
highly mistaken,'' he was quoted as saying.
	   Some newspapers have charged that Adami, justice minister since
January 1996, had sexual relations with prisoners and prostitutes.
	   Both Betchine and Adami are leading members of the National
Democratic Rally party, considered Zeroual's party.
	   The wrangling within the power elite has all but overshadowed
recently an Islamic insurgency that is in its seventh year.
Violence has left an estimated 75,000 people dead.
	   (rk-eg)
</TEXT>
