<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo-Agreement,0385 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Status of Milosevic's promises
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With Yugoslavia-Kosovo, Kosovo-Guerrillas &QL; 
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   The status Monday of promises that Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic must back up with evidence of compliance by NATO's
deadline _ pushed back to Oct. 27 _ or face renewed threat of
airstrikes for his crackdown in Kosovo:
	   _ Immediately halt all hostilities in Kosovo:
	   A new wave of violence over the weekend killed three Serb
policemen and wounded two, and both sides claimed a series of
attacks by the other that could not be independently confirmed.
	   No fullscale fighting has occurred in a month, but the weekend
violence brought more Serb army troops into central Kosovo on
Monday.
	   _ Withdraw forces and heavy armaments to levels before the
crackdown began Feb. 28:
	   NATO spy planes continued flying over Kosovo to check on the
status of pullouts. NATO says more Serb troops and police remain in
the province than are permitted.
	   Troops based in Pristina who were deployed in central Kosovo on
Sunday and Monday are allowed to be in the province.
	   _ Start serious talks with ethnic Albanians on self-rule:
	   No date for the start of talks has been announced. The two sides
have been holding separate discussions with U.S. envoy Christopher
Hill.
	   _ Help refugees return to their homes:
	   Some refugees have begun moving back to their villages but many
remain wary of Serb police forces, some of whom were accused in
massacres of civilians.
	   _ Allowing unhindered work by humanitarian organizations:
	   The U.N. refugee agency postponed two convoys Monday to assess
the security situation after the weekend violence. It said it
planned to send out the postponed convoys on Tuesday, along with
two other scheduled convoys.
	   _ Cooperating with the International War Crimes Tribunal:
	   U.N. war crimes investigators have received Yugoslav visas and
plan to return to Kosovo soon.
	   _ Allowing 2,000 international monitors into Kosovo to verify
that Yugoslavia is keeping its word:
	   An advance team for the monitors, to be overseen by the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, arrived
Saturday. OSCE officials in Pristina said 25 team members were in
the province as of midday Monday.
</TEXT>
