w1863 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Nigeria-Elections     10-19 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Elections </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nine parties to contest Nigerian elections
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By GILBERT DA COSTA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) _ Nine parties, including Nigeria's largest
opposition groups, have been allowed to register for local
elections in December _ a forerunner to this West African country's
ground-breaking presidential polling early next year, officials
said Monday.
	   National Electoral Commission chairman Ephraim Omukese Akpata
told journalists that the nine registered parties had fulfilled
criteria ensuring they have measurable support around Nigeria,
which since colonial times has been fiercely divided along ethnic
and regional lines.
	   Another 14 parties were excluded from running in the December 5
local government elections and the February 27 presidential poll
because they were too small or failed other requirements, Akpata
said without elaborating.
	   ``All the parties that are registered have scaled the ladder
that constituted the commission's screening exercise,'' Akpata said
during the brief announcement.
	   He took no questions from journalists and there was no immediate
reaction from the parties.
	   Registration for parties and voters ended Monday evening despite
complaints of a scarcity of registration materials that prevented
large numbers of people from signing up.
	   Officials said more people may be given the chance to register
in January prior to the presidential elections.
	   Since taking power in July, military ruler Gen. Abdulsalami
Abubakar has promised a sweeping democratic transition resulting in
a handover of power to elected civilians by the end of May.
	   There are no early favorites and many people are expected to
vote on regional and ethnic lines. Nigeria's military leaders,
primarily Muslims who hail from the north, have ruled the country
for all but 10 years since independence in 1960.
	   Abubakar took over in early June following the sudden death of
dictator Gen. Sani Abacha.
	   The mainly Christian south, where most of the country's oil
wealth is found, has long complained of military corruption and
misrule that has drained the region's resources and left many
people miserably poor.
	   Among the most well-known parties registered are the Alliance
for Democracy, a party believed to have strong support in Nigeria's
Yoruba-speaking southwest. It is led by Bola Ige, former governor
of the western state of Oyo.
	   The Peoples' Democratic Party, led by Nigeria's last civilian
vice-president Alex Akwueme, is strong in the north and east of the
country. Akwueme's administration lost 1993 elections that were
later annulled by the military.
	   Another group with northern support is the Peoples' Redemption
Party, led by Balarabe Musa, the respected former civilian governor
of Kaduna state.
	   Based in Nigeria's commercial capital of Lagos, Democratic
Advancement Movement led by former presidential candidate Tunji
Braithwaite is running on a platform of ensuring the rule of law is
upheld in Nigeria.
	   The other registered parties are: the All Peoples' Party, the
United Democratic Movement, the United Peoples' Party, the Movement
for Democracy and Justice, the National Solidarity Movement and the
Peoples' Redemption Party.
	   (gdc-gam-tjs)
</TEXT>
