<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Puerto Rico-Newspaper Wars,0266 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Puerto Rican capitol gets its fourth new newspaper in 18 months
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ The Puerto Rican capital's fourth
new daily newspaper in 18 months hit the stands Monday, joining a
rough-and-tumble race for readers in this U.S. territory.
	   El Mundo (The World) debuted with 96 pages and a cover story
focusing on reconstruction following Hurricane Georges. It is San
Juan's seventh newspaper.
	   The explosion in newspapers has been accompanied by a dogfight
of lawsuits as publishers spar over advertising, circulation
figures and government influence while gearing up for one of their
biggest stories of the decade _ a Dec. 13 vote on Puerto Rico's
relationship with the United States.
	   El Mundo is the third Puerto Rican newspaper to carry the name
and a globe logo. The original El Mundo published from 1917 to
1988, was resurrected in 1989 and closed again in 1990.
	   In an editorial introducing the newspaper, publisher Gaspar Roca
called the debut ``a risky venture.''
	   ``We have spared no effort to offer this newspaper to the good
and generous people of Puerto Rico,'' he wrote. Roca's Caribbean
International News Inc. also owns El Vocero, another daily.
	   In 1997, the island's English-language newspaper, The San Juan
Star, launched a Spanish edition. It later started an afternoon
newspaper, The Star Extra, and three regional editions.
	   They have been joined on news racks by Primera Hora, a color
newspaper published by El Nuevo Dia, the island's largest daily.
</TEXT>
