<SLUG> BC-Turkmenistan-Privatization </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkmenistan to privatize 48 state-owned companies
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The Central Asian nation of Turkmenistan will try
to sell 48 government-owned companies at a privatization auction
Saturday, the Interfax news agency reported Monday.
	   The report did not say what kind of businesses were to be sold.
	   Of the 4,800 state-run companies slated for privatization since
Turkmenistan gained independence with the 1991 Soviet collapse,
just 1,933 have moved to private hands, according to Turkmenistan's
National Statistics and Forecasting Institute.
	   The institute said privatization has lagged recently because the
government was mainly selling off unprofitable businesses that
require costly modernization and was setting too high a price for
them, Interfax said.
	   Turkmenistan, a former Soviet republic on the Caspian Sea, has
been slow to develop its economy, and remains largely impoverished,
despite vast oil reserves.
	   (adc)
