<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Guinea-Bissau-Fighting, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Aid workers warn of refugees' plight in Guinea-Bissau, as fighting
</HEADLINE>
resumes &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with aid workers warning of difficulties, other
details; RECASTS; CHANGES overline &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ Aid workers warned Monday that their
operations could be disrupted in Guinea-Bissau following fresh
reports of fighting between rebels and loyalist troops as part of a
four-month-old dispute in the west African nation.
	   ``The violent fighting will seriously affect food distribution
throughout the country,'' World Food Program spokesman Wadgi Othman
told The Associated Press by phone from Abidjan, capital of Ivory
Coast.
	   Meanwhile, a peace commission, led by Bissau's Roman Catholic
Bishop Septimio Ferrazzetta, asked to meet the rebels in a bid to
halt the latest fighting and reestablish a truce, Portuguese radio
TSF said, adding that thousands of residents were still fleeing the
capital.
	   The WFP and three other United Nations' relief agencies arrived
in Guinea-Bissau in August to secure the free flow of aid to the
refugees.
	   ``Last month people had started returning to Bissau, but this
situation crushes all hope of going back,'' Othama said.
	   Fighting restarted late Sunday and continued Monday in the
capital Bissau, as army dissidents and troops backing President
Joao Bernardo Vieira exchanged artillery fire.
	   ``The fighting has spread to the capital and is focused near the
presidential palace,'' Ana Paula Zacarias, a spokeswoman for the
Portuguese Foreign Ministry, said.
	   There were no details on casualties.
	   The conflict, which erupted June 7 in the tiny former Portuguese
colony wedged between Senegal and Guinea, displaced most of
Bissau's population of 300,000 to inland areas.
	   Hostilities began when Brig. Ansumane Mane was dismissed as army
chief-of-staff for allegedly running arms to Senegal's Casamance
separatists.
	   The rebels, led by Mane, seized Bissau's main army garrison and
airport, accusing Vieira of corruption and demanding that he step
down.
	   On July 26, both sides agreed to a cease-fire and stood by it
again in subsequent talks, brokered by west African and
Portuguese-speaking negotiators.
	   But the truce has been sporadically violated. Last week, five
rebels and one Senegalese soldier reportedly died in one outbreak
of shooting.
	   No reliable numbers have been made available for the total
number of people who died in the fighting.
	   (cp/cg)
</TEXT>
