<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Caribbean Red Stripe,0388 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Champions Leeward Islands beat Guyana in Red Stripe Bowl final
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By HOWARD CAMPBELL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   OCHO RIOS, Jamaica (AP) _ Guyana squandered a good start and
faltered to 226 for seven off 50 overs against the Leeward Islands
at halftime Monday in the final of the Caribbean's Red Stripe Bowl
one-day cricket tournament.
	   The Guyanese lost their way in late innings after openers
Clayton Lambert and Andrew Gonsalves had posted 108 for the first
wicket in aggressive fashion. This after captain Carl Hooper had
won the toss and batted at the Kaiser Sports Club, near the
Jamaican resort of Ocho Rios.
	   Lambert was the dominant partner, punching 66 off 72 deliveries
in an innings that included one six and seven boundaries. The
lefthander looked in ominous form before being run out attempting a
quick single in the 23rd over.
	   Gonsalves played some attractive strokes but he also went via
the run-out route three overs later after making 41 which contained
six boundaries. Casually crossing for a single he was caught short
of his crease by a throw from Leewards captain Stuart Williams.
	   The remainder of the Guyanese batsmen failed to capitalize on
the good start given them by Lambert and Gonsalves. Though sharing
in a third wicket stand of 41, star batsmen Hooper (25) and
Shivnarine Chanderpaul (29) never looked threatening as the
Leewards fought their way back into contention through superb
fielding and good bowling.
	   Leading the attack for the Leewards, last year's Red Stripe
champions, was offspinner Anthony Lake who captured two wickets for
42 runs.
	   The Leewards won their way into the final after appealing the
Jamaica Cricket Board's decision that Trinidad and Tobago should
have contested the match.
	   Trinidad and Tobago were declared winners after Saturday's
semi-final against the Leewards was halted midway through the
Trinidadians' innings.
	   Match referee Hugh Perry ruled that Trinidad and Tobago were
winners of the match due to a superior run rate.
	   But the Leewards' management charged that Perry had used the
wrong formula to determine the run rate. Their appeal was upheld
late Sunday despite much confusion and controversy. Trinidad and
Tobago reportedly are considering taking legal action.
</TEXT>
