<SLUG> BC-Syria-Prisoner </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Amnesty: Syria's longest-serving prisoner hospitalized
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Syria's longest-serving prisoner, a
Palestinian activist who was first jailed in 1966, has been
hospitalized after falling unconscious during a three-week hunger
strike, Amnesty International said Monday.
	   Abdel-Majid Zaghmout, 54, was admitted to Al-Muwasat hospital in
Damascus last week during a hunger strike to protest his detention,
the human rights group said in a statement.
	   Zaghmout was also suffering from internal bleeding from an
untreated ulcer and an ear infection due to unhygienic prison
conditions in Adra prison outside the capital, Amnesty said.
	   Amnesty said the hospital offers ``no specialist medical care to
deal with serious ear problems,'' and authorities are refusing to
allow him care in a specialized state health institution.
	   Syrian officials would not comment on the report.
	   Amnesty called on Syrian officials to free Zaghmout and to
ensure that he is ``guaranteed access to any specialist medical
care that he needs.''
	   Zaghmout, a former member of Fatah, the mainstream Palestine
Liberation Organization faction, was arrested on May 10, 1966 and
charged with the murder of a Palestinian guerrilla leader.
	   He was sentenced to death later that year by a military court
after what Amnesty called a ``grossly unfair trial.''
	   The sentence was commuted in 1989 to a prison term equal to the
time that he had already spent in custody. It is unclear why he
remains in prison.
	   Syrian jails hold hundreds of political prisoners, Amnesty has
said.
