<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Czech-Presidential Apology Request,0369 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Controversial mayor seeks an apology from the president
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NADIA RYBAROVA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) _ On the eve of an official visit to
Britain, President Vaclav Havel rebuked a mayor who had suggested
to wall in buildings housing unruly Gypsy families in his town. Now
the mayor wants Havel to apologize.
	   The plan to build walls around Gypsy, or Roma, settlements in
Usti nad Labem in northern Bohemia was first aired by mayor
Ladislav Hruska in May, triggering a wave of protests _ and visits
_ by Czech and foreign reporters and human rights activists.
	   Havel did not comment on the issue before his Czech radio
address Sunday.
	   ``It can happen that a mayor appears who behaves as if the town
(he runs) belonged to him,'' Havel said in the broadcast. ``He
speaks for his electorate and probably thinks that it's his
obligation to share all the prejudices, including the racist ones,
the residents of his town harbor.''
	   Speaking one day before leaving for Britain, Havel also accused
mayor Hruska of damaging the image of the Czech Republic abroad.
The British government repeatedly has indicated it may request
visas from Czech citizens.
	   Rather than publicly rescind his controversial proposal, the
mayor accuses Havel of blaming all citizens of Usti nad Labem, 100
kilometers (60 miles) northwest of Prague, of being racists and
wants the president to apologize.
	   In a statement sent to The Associated Press, Hruska, said, ``I
ask President Vaclav Havel to apologize to the residents of Usti
nad Labem,'' adding, ``they have always shown ... that most of them
don't harbor prejudices, including racist ones the president
ascribes to all of them.''
	   ``I repeat ... that I always will defend the rights of all the
citizens regardless of their nationality, race or color,'' Hruska
said.
	   Hruska's original plan came after residents complained that Roma
families in his town are violent, noisy, dirty and produce too much
garbage.
	   While such a wall has not been built and likely never will, many
human rights activists have accused Usti 's municipality of
sanctioning the building of a new ghetto.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Czech-Presidential Apology Request; CT:i; 
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:ASIA;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
