<SLUG> BC-Italy-Politics, 2nd Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
President formally taps D'Alema as next premier
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS more on policies, timing, Vatican objections &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro on Monday formally
asked former Communist Massimo D'Alema to form Italy's 56th
government since World War II.
	   Scalfaro's request came after D'Alema reported to the president
that he has assembled a parliamentary majority in days of hard
bargaining with centrist and leftists parties.
	   D'Alema is expected to announce his Cabinet choices Tuesday or
Wednesday and go to Parliament for the vote of confidence that
would make him premier in time to attend the European Union Summit
on Friday and Saturday.
	   One of D'Alema's first appearances as premier-designate will be
to join Scalfaro in meeting with Pope John Paul II Tuesday at the
presidential palace.
	   The Vatican newspaper, Osservatore Romano, was sharply critical
of the decision to tap D'Alema because of his Communist past.
	   ``Fifty years after the momentous victory of freedom and
democracy over communism, the head of state has entrusted the task
of forming a government to a man from the apparatus of the former
Italian Communist Party,'' it wrote on Sunday.
	   D'Alema was asked Monday if he would try to clear the air with
the pope.
	   ``I have had no arguments with the Holy Father,'' D'Alema said
at a news conference. ``I have nothing to clear up.''
	   	   At his meeting Monday evening with Scalfaro, D'Alema outlined
policies in line with those of Premier Romano Prodi, who guided
Italy into the European economic and currency union.
	   D'Alema also vowed to try again at constitutional reform, a
project he spearheaded but which the conservative opposition sank
earlier this year.
	   In a platform released by D'Alema's office, the parties backing
him pledged to pursue privatization at the pace Prodi had set, to
strive for a 35-hour work week and to tackle unemployment with
government funds linked to private investment in infrastructure
projects.
