<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq-Inspectors,0391 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iraq steps up campaign against U.N. monitors
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By LEON BARKHO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Iraqi officials lashed out at U.N. arms
monitors Monday, saying they act unprofessionally and in one case
turned on music and danced as they examined a missile production
site.
	   Iraq repeatedly has accused U.N. weapons inspectors of espionage
and on Aug. 5 ordered an end to surprise inspections by the arms
experts, effectively banning all searches for elements of its past
weapons programs.
	   Iraq has recently mounted a campaign to discredit the remaining
inspectors, who are only allowed to visit weapons sites where the
United Nations already has surveillance equipment installed.
	   One Iraqi official, Kahlil Hameed, accused the monitors of
acting unprofessionally by turning on cassette recorders and
dancing in August while examining a missile site.
	   Hammed also said monitors used their personal cameras to take
photographs of civilians, passing cars and visitors to the missile
production site that he administers.
	   Iraqi authorities arranged the interview with Hameed to back up
accusations by Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz that the inspectors
engaged in espionage. Aziz made that claim in a letter to U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan released Saturday.
	   U.N. weapons officials in Baghdad were not available for
comment.
	   Sudat Mohammed of the Iraqi National Monitoring Directorate,
which coordinates activities for the remaining 40 inspectors in
Iraq, said that some inspectors carried cameras and photographed
army movements and activities in and around Iraqi weapons sites.
	   ``Incidents like this unfortunately indicate that the inspectors
use the authority and mandate given to them in a bad manner to
collect information,'' Mohammed said.
	   In a related development, the official Iraqi News Agency said
Monday that Iraqi President Saddam Hussein and his cabinet reviewed
the inspections.
	   The cabinet also reviewed contacts with Annan to resolve the
current row over spot inspections, the agency reported.
	   The United Nations imposed sweeping economic sanctions against
Iraq after Baghdad's 1990 invasion of Kuwait. The sanctions will
not be lifted until the inspectors verify that Baghdad has
eliminated its weapons of mass destruction.
</TEXT>
