<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-Pinochet </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With BC-Britain-Pinochet
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Frei and Aznar meet as judge expands Pinochet arrest warrant &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BAYONA, Spain (AP) _ Chilean President Eduardo Frei and Spain's
Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar met Monday as the controversy raged
over the detention in London of former dictator Augusto Pinochet at
the behest of a Spanish judge.
	   The Chilean government has protested the action of Judge
Baltasar Garzon that prompted the British police to detain the
82-year-old former military chief while he was in a London clinic
recovering from back surgery last Friday.
	   Garzon, who may soon travel to London to interrogate Pinochet,
on Monday widened the basis of his original detention request to
cover the disappearance of 94 people, mostly Chileans.
	   Another Spanish Judge Manuel Garcia Castellon, who is
investigating human rights violations in Chile, has also applied to
question Pinochet in London.
	   Any request for Pinochet's extradition from Britain, must be
approved first by Spain's National Court and then Aznar's cabinet
before being presented to British authorities, who would have the
final word.
	   There was no official confirmation that Aznar and Frei would
meet to specifically discuss the Pinochet case while they are in
this northwestern town for talks with fellow Christian Democratic
leaders from Argentina, Ecuador, Colombia and Costa Rica.
	   ``The (democratic) institutions of Spain were born after 40
years of dictatorship without going through the kind of human
rights trials that are demanded of us in Latin America,'' Frei told
reporters here referring to the regime of late Gen. Francisco
Franco in Spain.
	   Frei's was complaining that elected Spanish governments
overseeing the transition to democracy after the death of Franco in
1975 had not been required to deal with politically delicate human
rights legal processes such as that looming over Pinochet.
	   Frei was expected to return to Chile immediately after the
Bayona meeting having canceled a 24-hour private visit in Madrid
owing to the Pinochet's arrest, the Chilean Embassy in Madrid said.
	   Meanwhile, Spanish government spokesman Josep Pique said the
government would not be commenting on the issue as it was a matter
for the judiciary.
	   On Monday, Aznar made no reference to Pinochet and would only
say that the consolidation of democracy in Argentina and Chile were
``bearing fruit.''
	   In the past Aznar has been unenthusiastic about Judge Garzon's
investigations relating to Chile or Argentina.
	   Garzon is pursuing an investigation into the activities of the
so-called Operation Condor through which Latin American
dictatorships allegedly coordinated campaigns to crack down on
leftists during the 1970s and early 1980s.
	   His investigation focuses on events in Argentina.
	   Argentine President Carlos Menem, was also in Bayona, backed
Frei saying Spanish judges ``had nothing to do'' with supposed
crimes committed in his country.
	   (jt/cg)
</TEXT>
