<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-Pinochet,1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede BAYONA
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Spanish judge takes another step toward extraditing Pinochet &QL; 
 &UR; With Britain-Pinochet &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo MAD101, MAD105 &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: AMs; RECASTS with details on judge's new order &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ A Spanish judge on Monday took another step
toward having former Chilean dictator Augusto Pinochet extradited
from Britain to Spain to face charges of genocide, torture and
terrorism.
	   Judge Baltasar Garzon, whose arrest order Friday prompted
British police to detain the aging Pinochet in London, fleshed out
that original document with specific charges involving 94 alleged
victims of Pinochet's regime, most of them Chileans.
	   The original order said Pinochet, who was in London recovering
from back surgery, was responsible for the death of Spaniards and
people of other nationalities. But it cited only one specific case,
the kidnapping and disappearance of a Chilean dissident.
	   ``This broadens the provisional and unconditional detention of
Augusto Pinochet Ugarte for the facts described in this
resolution,'' the judge said in the document, which was sent on to
Britain.
	   Garzon is probing Pinochet's alleged role in so-called Operation
Condor in which South American military juntas in Chile, Argentina,
Uruguay and elsewhere teamed up to snuff out dissent in each
other's countries in the 1970s and 1980s.
	   Garzon may travel soon to London to interrogate Pinochet.
Another judge, Manuel Garcia Castellon, who is probing human rights
violations in Chile, could also go to quiz him.
	   Garzon is relying on a Spanish law that allows prosecution of
alleged genocide no matter where it occurs.
	   Spanish prosecutors say he has no jurisdiction outside of Spain
and on Monday filed a procedural motion to try to block him. But
while a court considers it, the arrest warrant against Pinochet
stands, lawyers said.
	   Garzon's addendum accused Pinochet of ``physical elimination,
disappearances, kidnappings and torture'' of perceived leftists.
	   It said they were of various nationalities _ Spanish, Argentine,
British, U.S., Chilean and others _ but named only 94, almost all
of them Chileans.
	   Private lawyers working with Garzon said the addendum is in
itself a sufficient legal basis for Britain to begin consider
extraditing Pinochet, who is 82.
	   Garzon may also issue an extradition request via the Spanish
government, the lawyers said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
	   In this case it must be approved by the Justice Ministry and the
cabinet of center-right Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar, they said.
	   Aznar has frowned upon Garzon's probe, and has declined to say
if he would approve an extradition request.
	   If he does back it, Britain would have the final say.
	   Chile's government has protested Pinochet's arrest saying he had
diplomatic immunity. Chilean President Eduardo Frei met Monday with
Aznar in the northern Spanish town of Bayona but it was not
immediately known if they discussed the Pinochet case.
	   They were there for talks with fellow Christian Democratic
leaders from Argentina, Ecuador, Colombia and Costa Rica after a
weekend Ibero-American summit in Portugal.
	   A Chilean government report issued after Pinochet left office
said 4,299 political opponents were killed or disappeared during
his 17-year rule.
	   Pinochet has immunity from prosecution at home because a
constitution he guided to enactment before stepping down as
president in 1990 made him a senator for life.
	   (dw/cg) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
