<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Oil Explosion, 8th Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nigerian town devastated as gas scavengers killed by fireball
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS new 8th graf to UPDATE with hospitals overwhelmed.
CORRECTS typo in `devastated' in overline. Pickup 8th graf
previous, `A mass grave ...' &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos planned
 &UR; By FRANK AIGBOGUN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JESSE, Nigeria (AP) _ Hundreds of people converged on this small
Nigerian town over the weekend, drawn by rumors of spilled gasoline
free for the taking _ and at least 500 were killed when the fuel
erupted into a ball of fire, officials said Monday.
	   With dozens of charred, unidentified bodies littering the town
and flames still occasionally flaring up to 20 meters (65 feet) in
the air, authorities began the grim task Monday of burying those
incinerated by the ball of fire.
	   Firefighters stopped fighting the flames and waited for the
blaze, which spread thick black smoke for miles (kilometers)
around, to burn itself out.
	   Grieving relatives also came to Jesse, about 300 kilometers (180
miles) southeast of Lagos, searching for the charred remains of
their loved ones.
	   ``It is finished,'' cried Charity Unurhoro, after finding the
horribly burned bodies of her mother and brother. ``Now everything
is over for me.''
	   As she cried, a man told a young relative to fetch a wheelbarrow
to take the corpses home for burial.
	   The fire, which began Saturday as the residents tried to scoop
gasoline spilling from a pipeline, killed at least 500 people and
left at least 100 hospitalized, military officials said.
	   The area's hospitals _ most of which only have a handful of
doctors and nurses and little in the way of burn care _ were
overwhelmed by the disaster, with doctors overworked and medicine
in short supply, local officials said.
	    &UR; Pickup 8th graf previous, `A mass grave ...'
	   (fa-tjs)
