<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Mad Cow </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Britain outlines high cost of ''mad cow'' disease
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ The cost of tackling ''mad cow'' disease might
reach 4.6 billion pounds (dlrs 7.8 billion) by 2002, a British
government official said Monday.
	   But about 45 percent of that sum will be reimbursed by the
European community, said Jeffrey Rooker, an official with the
Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food, in a written reply to
a question from the House of Commons.
	   The cost is estimated from 1996 when the European Union banned
British beef exports. The ban came after Britain announced a
possible link between bovine spongiform encephalopathy, or BSE, and
the fatal, brain-wasting Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease. The disease has
killed 27 people in Britain since 1995.
	   Hundreds of thousands of cattle have been slaughtered and their
carcasses destroyed since March 1996 as part of the government's
attempt to eradicate the disease.
	   But Britain has been actively lobbying the European Union to
ease its ban on British beef exports by the end of the year.
	   	   (mb) 	   
</TEXT>
