<SLUG> BC-Britain-Royal Yacht </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Britannia opens to the public
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RETRANSMITTING to correct overline &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LEITH, Scotland (AP) _ One of the designers and an original
crewman of the former royal yacht Britannia helped open the ship to
the paying public Monday.
	   Britannia, which served as a traveling home for members of
Britain's royal family for nearly 44 years until its retirement in
December, is expected to attract 200,000 visitors a year.
	   The 412-foot (125-meter) yacht had grown too costly to operate
and has been permanently docked here.
	   James Houston, who worked on designing Britannia and was
visiting the ship on his 64th birthday, and Andrew Brown, a crewman
at the ship's launch in 1954, were first on board at the invitation
of the vessel's general manager, Bob Downie.
	   The first paying visitor, Karen Standland of Nottingham,
England, said she felt the former royal yacht was presented in a
``dignified'' way.
	   ``It's all remarkably well-done,'' she said, adding, ``I'm
struck by how small the officers' cabins were.''
	   Access to Britannia is via a onshore visitor center where people
will be able to learn about the yacht's history with the help of
interactive displays. Visitors will be guided around the yacht and
see all areas of the ship from the galleys to the bedrooms.
	   ``Over 95 percent of the royal collection is on board,'' Downie
said. ``People will be able to see it exactly as it was.''
	   Admission is 6.50 pounds (dlrs 11) for adults and 3.75 pounds
(dlrs 6.40) for children, with a family ticket offered for 18
pounds (dlrs 30).
	   (ms-kg)
</TEXT>
