<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Train, 6th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Egypt suspends railway officials after 47 killed in train accident
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs, UPDATES with suspension of railway officials, details &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo LON101, CAI101-8
 &UR; By TAREK EL-TABLAWY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KAFR EL-DAWAR, Egypt (AP) _ The Egyptian government suspended
five top railway officials Monday after a train jumped its rails
and slammed into a crowded town square, killing 47 people.
	   Transportation Minister Suleiman Metwally ordered the suspension
of the officials, including the national head of railways and the
managers in the province where the accident occurred, pending an
investigation into the accident.
	   The train flew off the rails as it pulled into a siding in the
station of Kafr el-Dawar town, 30 kilometers (20 miles) southeast
of the port city of Alexandria.
	   It crashed through a barricade and into the town square, killing
47 and injuring 104 people, police officials said. They dismissed
earlier reports of as many as 52 dead, saying that in some cases,
bodies were cut in two and counted twice in preliminary death
tolls.
	   A preliminary investigation indicated that the accident was
caused by a faulty brake system.
	   It said that passengers had disrupted brake linkages between
cars, causing them to fail. People often hop on packed Egyptian
trains and ride on the roof or between the cars.
	   Witnesses said the train was speeding when it pulled into the
station, and that the driver was wildly blowing the whistle and
yelling for bystanders to get out of the way.
	   Rescue teams ended their search for survivors Monday after
lifting the last car of the train with mobile cranes.
	   Pools of blood and shredded bloodstained clothing could be seen
beneath the wreckage.
	   Five mangled bodies, including that of a young boy, were found
beneath the last three cars of the train, witnesses said.
	   Hundreds of citizens crowded the square to help in the rescue
efforts.
	   Residents accused the authorities of neglect.
	   ``No one came until 8:15,'' said Khaled Mohammed Lotfi.
``Everyone you see working here is a local man. We asked them to
call the Defense Ministry to bring in soldiers to help, but they
called us crazy.''
	   Most of the dead were bystanders in the town and the majority of
the injured were passengers on the train, said Nabih Yousef
Shaltout, head of health care in the local province of Buheira.
	   The train, which was traveling south from Alexandria, left the
rails when the driver changed tracks at high speed, the Interior
Ministry said in a statement.
	   The train crashed through a wall beside the railway, shot into
the air, hit a war memorial in the square and slammed into seven
shops, witnesses said.
	   When the train hit the buildings, ``it sounded like thunder,''
said Hany Roushdy, a teen-ager who saw the crash.
	   Egyptian railways have suffered a series of accidents in the
past four years. The most serious was in December 1995, when one
train crashed into another in fog south of Cairo, killing 75 people
and injuring 76.
 &UR; pvs-mae-tt-lm 	   
