<SLUG> BC-Israel-Explosion, 10th Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Grenades injure dozens at Israeli bus station
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with report assailant said he was sent by Hamas &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos TLV101-108
 &UR; By LAURIE COPANS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEERSHEBA, Israel (AP) _ A Palestinian man threw two hand
grenades near a bus stop crowded with Israel soldiers Monday
morning, injuring at least 64 people during a critical point in a
Mideast peace summit in Maryland.
	   In response to the attack, Israel suspended talks with the
Palestinians on all matters unrelated to security issues and
Israel's prime minister said he would not remain at the talks for
an ``unlimited period of time.''
	   Three victims of the attack were in serious condition after the
rush hour assault in the desert town of Beersheba 50 miles (83
kilometers) south of Jerusalem, and many soldiers were among the
wounded.
	   After the 8 a.m. (0600 gmt) blasts, army-issue olive duffel bags
and clothes were seen strewn on the pavement near a glass-covered
bus stop. A soldier's polished black boots, with the socks stuffed
inside, were left behind on a traffic island.
	   There were conflicting reports on how the assailant was caught.
	   Some witnesses said that as the Palestinian fled, he ran into a
bus turning the corner. A bus driver said he ran down the attacker
with his bus. Israel TV's Channel Two showed footage of a bus whose
glass door was shattered by the impact.
	   However, a construction worker, Avi Friedman, said he jumped the
man from behind and wrestled him to the ground.
	   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat called Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu after receiving word of the attack. Arafat said
he regretted the incident and ordered an investigation, according
to a statement by Netanyahu's office.
	   Netanyahu, who received the call during a meeting with U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, said he appreciated the word
but that now, more than ever, real action by the Palestinians was
needed to fight terrorism.
	   ``In order to achieve peace, there is a need for a firm struggle
and a clear order to everyone in the Palestinian Authority,
especially Jibril Rajoub, to act on all security matters,''
Netanyahu said in a statement, referring to Arafat's West Bank
security chief.
	   In response to the attack, Netanyahu decided to postpone a
negotiation session that had been scheduled for Monday on the
opening of a Palestinian airport in the Gaza Strip.
	   ``For progress to be achieved on other issues, we must first
focus on security and terrorism. We are awaiting answers from the
Palestinians today. We do not plan to stay at Wye Plantation for an
unlimited period of time,'' Netanyahu said in a press statement
issued from his office in Jerusalem.
	   Rajoub said the assailant was a 29-year-old father of five from
the West Bank town of Hebron. He said the man was a supporter of
the Islamic militant group Hamas and was imprisoned twice for
activities linked to the group.
	   Israel radio quoted the country's police minister, Avigdor
Kahalani as saying that the assailant told investigators that Hamas
had sent him to carry out the attack.
	   Hamas founder, 14th graf pvs
