<SLUG> BC-UN-Sierra Leone,0524 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN chief condemns barbarism in Sierra Leone and urges surrender
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By EDITH M. LEDERER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan condemned
``acts of barbarism'' by rebels in Sierra Leone and urged them
Monday to lay down their arms and surrender.
	   In a report to the Security Council, Annan said human rights
abuses committed by the rebels have created a ``humanitarian
emergency'' in the West African nation and continue to cause
widespread dislocation of the local population.
	   ``In the last two months the northern province has seen a
resurgence of rebel activity, including atrocities, with no sign of
weakening in rebel resolve, numbers or organization,'' Annan said.
	   The current concentration of rebels in the northwest indicates
that they may be preparing for a major strike against Makeni or
Port Loko, which would sever the main route from neighboring Guinea
used to supply the West African peacekeeping force in Sierra Leone,
he said.
	   U.N. humanitarian experts estimate that 250,000 people have been
displaced since the intervention of the Nigerian-led peacekeeping
force in February, an increase of about 70,000 since August. And
Annan said there are fears a considerable number of displaced
people remain uncounted.
	   Sierra Leone, one of the world's poorest countries, has been
plagued by civil war since the early 1990s.
	   A rebel junta which seized power from the democratically elected
government in May 1997 was driven from office by a Nigerian-led
peacekeeping force. Although the elected president's return to
power early this year was hailed as a victory for democracy in West
Africa, it has not ended the bloodshed.
	   U.N. observers received an escalating number of reports in
September of mutilations, amputations, summary executions,
abductions and house burnings, Annan said, noting that in a single
week 20 villages were attacked and destroyed in northwestern Sierra
Leone.
	   ``I am particularly outraged by the senseless acts of terror
perpetrated against children, such as the amputation of limbs of
boys and girls as young as six years of age, and support the
efforts to bring to justice the authors of these especially
abhorrent crimes,'' he said.
	   As a result of the continuing military conflict, the government
has made little progress in disarming, demobilizing and
reintegrating soldiers which are essential for the long-term
stability of the country, Annan said.
	   The secretary general also expressed ``deep concern'' about
instability on the border between Sierra Leone and Liberia and
urged both governments to exercise ``maximum restraint'' and pursue
dialogue.
	   If both countries agree, he said, the deployment of peacekeeping
troops and U.N. military observers at the border ``could help to
stabilize the situation and restore mutual confidence.''
	   On a day that 34 military officers were executed in Sierra Leone
for crimes linked to the 1997 coup, Annan expressed concern that
those sentenced to death by military courts had no right of appeal.
</TEXT>
