<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-Pinochet, 1st Ld-Writethru,0379 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede BAYONA
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Spanish judge takes another step toward extraditing Pinochet &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS with details on judge's new order &QL; 
 &UR; With Britain-Pinochet &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo MAD101, MAD105 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ A Spanish judge on Monday moved closer to
having former Chilean dictator Augusto Pinochet extradited from
Britain to Spain on charges of genocide, torture and terrorism.
	   Judge Baltasar Garzon, whose arrest order Friday prompted
British police to detain the aging Pinochet in London, added in a
second document sent to Britain specific charges related to 94
alleged victims of Pinochet's regime, most of them Chileans.
	   The original order said Pinochet, who is in London recovering
from back surgery, was responsible for the death of Spaniards and
others. But it had cited only one specific case, the kidnapping and
disappearance of a Chilean dissident.
	   Another Spanish Judge Manuel Garcia Castellon, who is
investigating human rights violations in Chile, has also applied to
question Pinochet in London.
	   Any request for his extradition must be approved first by
Spain's National Court and then by the cabinet of Prime Minister
Jose Maria Aznar before being presented to British authorities, who
would have the final word.
	   Garzon has 40 days from Friday to present a formal extradition
request.
	   Garzon is probing Pinochet's alleged role in Operation Condor in
which juntas in Chile, Argentina, Uruguay and elsewhere cooperated
to snuff out dissent in each other's countries in the 1970s and
1980s.
	   Aznar's government has opposed the probes by Garzon and Garcia
Castellon, saying they could upset delicate political dynamics in
countries that suffered years of military rule.
	   On Monday, Spanish prosecutors moved to try to stop the judge's
planned trip to London.
	   While Garzon is relying on a Spanish law that allows prosecution
of alleged genocide no matter where it occurs, Spanish prosecutors
say he has no jurisdiction outside Spain.
	   Chile's government has protested Pinochet's arrest saying he had
diplomatic immunity abroad and immunity from prosecution at home
because a constitution he guided to enactment before stepping down
as president in 1990 made him a senator for life.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
