r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Olympics-Dopin     10-19 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Olympics-Doping-German Medals,0637 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USOC to ask for `medal recognition' for swim relay beaten by East
</HEADLINE>
Germans &QL; 
 &UR; By LARRY SIDDONS &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Four U.S. swimmers from two decades ago may be
getting Olympic gold medals that authorities believe were lost to
drug use by East German athletes.
	   U.S. Olympic Committee president Bill Hybl said Monday that he
was preparing to ask the International Olympic Committee to give
``appropriate medal recognition'' to the 1976 American women's
400-meter medley relay team, which finished second to East Germany
at the Summer Games in Montreal.
	   Hybl said the USOC would not ask that the East German quartet of
Ulrike Richter, Hannelore Anke, Andrea Pollack and Kornelia Ender
relinquish its title.
	   But he said that a German court case investigating athlete
doping in the old East German sports system offered ``conclusive
proof'' that the gold-medal team had an unfair edge.
	   The East Germans won the race in 4 minutes, 7.95 seconds, taking
5 1/2 seconds off the old world record and beating the U.S. team of
Linda Jezek, Lauri Siering, Camile Wright and Shirley Babeshoff by
6.6 seconds.
	   Hybl said the committee was awaiting court documents that it
believes will show irrefutably that Pollack, who swam the third
leg, was boosted by anabolic steroids, which are banned by the IOC
and most other sports organizations.
	   Steroids help build muscle mass and allow an athlete to rebound
faster from injuries. The German courts have heard testimony that
East German athletes were routinely fed steroids disguised as
vitamins, and five doctors and coaches have admitted giving
steroids to athletes as young as 12 years old.
	   ``From 1968 through 1988, there was state-sponsored doping
throughout the East German sports system,'' Hybl said. ``The fact
is that there probably were 10,000 athletes involved in the
system.''
	   Babeshoff was the premier U.S. women's swimmer in the mid-1970s
but was repeatedly stymied in international competition. Between
1972-76, she won four gold medals and 13 silvers in the Olympics
and world championships, with 10 of those runner-up finishes behind
East German swimmers.
	   Because the doping apparently took place without the athletes'
knowledge, Hybl said, the USOC would not ask that the original gold
medals be withdrawn.
	   But Hybl said he would ask IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch
within the next 2-3 weeks to take action ``out of fairness and
competition in the Olympic spirit.''
	   ``We are going to pursue having appropriate medal recognition,''
Hybl said. ``We support our athletes.''
	   The East German relay team passed drug tests at the Montreal
Games and the IOC for years has refused to even consider changing
results that might have been tainted by doping.
	   It threw Canadian 100-meter gold medalist Ben Johnson out of the
1988 Games in Seoul after he flunked a drug test and later admitted
under oath that he had been on steroids for years. But the IOC
allowed him to keep his bronze relay medal from the 1984 Los
Angeles Olympics because he passed a drug test there.
	   Last January, as court evidence of East German doping mounted,
Samaranch said the IOC would consider altering its records and
medals standings in cases were there was specific proof of
cheating. It was a major change for an organization that values
tradition and history.
	   And, while rumors of drug use by scores of athletes from many
countries have circulated for years, Hybl said the USOC would not
ask for a large-scale alteration of Olympic races.
	   ``We are going to support our athletes on a case-by-case basis
where there is conclusive proof through either conviction or
confession in court,'' he said.
</TEXT>
