<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-Hurricane Hero,0388 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dominicans look to Sosa as a hurricane hero
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JOSE MONEGRO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic _ The party's already begun in
the Dominican Republic, where Sammy Sosa, at last, is coming home
as a much-needed national hero.
	   The Dominican-born Chicago Cubs slugger has been busy in the
United States, basking in the glow of his 66-home run season,
receiving the keys to New York City, throwing a ceremonial first
pitch in the World Series and raising funds for hurricane relief.
	   On Tuesday, it's Dominicans' turn.
	   ``Many times, Sosa made us feel happy with his home runs,'' said
Miguel Contreras, a bar patron in Santo Domingo. ``Now it's right
that we make him feel good.''
	   In a country still coping with the ravages of Hurricane Georges,
the government proclaimed Sosa's homecoming Tuesday a day of
national celebration. Thousands of well-wishers will get free bus
rides to Santo Domingo's international airport to cheer Sosa's
arrival.
	   In Santo Domingo, hundreds of motorists cruised the streets,
sporting the magic number ``66'' on their windshields. In Sosa's
storm-battered hometown of San Pedro de Macoris, 40 miles (66
kilometers) east of Santo Domingo, residents have plastered the
seaside boulevard's trees and walls with posters of Sosa.
	   President Leonel Fernandez planned to present Sosa with the
Order of Duarte, Sanchez and Mella, the Caribbean country's highest
civilian honor, before Sosa heads to San Pedro, where he will
distribute relief aid to storm victims.
	   Dominicans followed every step of Sosa and Mark McGwire's battle
to surpass Roger Maris' Major League record of 61 home runs in a
season. Each home run, each strikeout was chronicled in
excruciating detail by the country's newspapers.
	   While McGwire took the crown with 70 homers, Sosa's final home
runs provided the only cause for celebration while Hurricane
Georges raked the nation on Sept. 22. The storm killed at least 283
people in the Dominican Republic and left more than 100,000
homeless.
	   For a day, at least, Dominicans look forward to forgetting the
pain and pressure of life after the hurricane. ``I wouldn't miss
the opportunity to welcome Sammy for anything,'' Contreras said.
</TEXT>
