<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Football-DeBerg's Journey,0589 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
44-year-old DeBerg might just be the starter in Atlanta
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By PAUL NEWBERRY &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SUWANEE, Georgia (AP) _ Try selling this story to Hollywood.
	   A 44-year-old who hasn't played in the National Football League
since 1993 decides to come out of retirement. He manages to find a
team that will give him a tryout, then plays well enough in
training camp to earn a job as the backup quarterback.
	   Now, here's where the plot gets really interesting. The starter
goes down with an injury, so the aging quarterback finds himself
taking snaps for a 5-1 team.
	   Steve DeBerg, the role belongs to you.
	   ``The whole thing has been kind of an amazing adventure,'' said
DeBerg, who will start for the Atlanta Falcons if Chris Chandler's
aching left shoulder doesn't heal before this weekend's game
against the New York Jets. ``A lot of what has happened has really
surprised me.''
	   Coach Dan Reeves admitted Monday he doesn't know what to expect
if he has to start a quarterback who is only a decade younger than
himself and just a few years away from qualifying for a senior
citizen's discount.
	   ``We're dealing with the unknown,'' Reeves said. ``Until he
plays a full game, no one is really going to know for sure. I can't
answer that question. I just know that I'm not that concerned about
it. I think he understands and knows what it takes. He's been there
before.''
	   Already, DeBerg has played a key role in the Falcons matching
the best start in team history.
	   On Sunday, after Chandler hobbled off the field in excruciating
pain late in the first half, DeBerg took off his baseball cap,
slipped on his helmet and made sure Atlanta remained tied for first
in the NFC West with a 31-23 victory over the New Orleans Saints.
	   ``It was very exciting,'' DeBerg said, reflecting on his
performance a day later at the Falcons' suburban training complex.
``It was frustrating for me in the third quarter when things
weren't going as well as I expected or hoped for. But the team was
playing so well, I had a chance to kind of settle down and get
things going.''
	   Indeed, the third quarter was like a horror movie, with DeBerg
as the star. The Falcons were leading 17-14 when he was sacked in
the end zone for a safety. He completed only one of four passes in
the quarter _ the lone completion resulting in a 3-yard loss _ and
guided the Falcons to minus-15 yards in offense.
	   In the fourth quarter, however, the story took an amazing twist.
DeBerg completed all four of his passes, including his first
touchdown since '93 and a key third-down throw that allowed the
Falcons to run out the clock.
	   ``I really have been preparing myself because I know if
something does happen, this team is going to depend on me to win
the football game,'' said DeBerg, who was 7-of-10 for 60 yards.
``I've seen a lot of backup quarterbacks who kind of take the easy
way out and don't prepare themselves. When the opportunity presents
itself, they're not prepared mentally or physically.''
	   DeBerg certainly hasn't taken the easy way out. He retired after
the 1993 season, a 16-year career seemingly over at age 40, but he
maintained his physical conditioning, kept throwing a football in
his spare time and finally talked himself into trying a comeback.
	   If Chandler can't play against the Jets, DeBerg will make his
first start since Dec. 13, 1993, when he subbed for the injured Dan
Marino in Miami.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Football-DeBerg's Journey; CT:s; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
