<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Football-Flutie's Future,0510 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Flutie's magical comeback wins stir quarterback debate
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JEFF GOODMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer

<TEXT>
	   ORCHARD PARK, New York (AP) _ The last thing the Buffalo Bills
want is a quarterback controversy. Doug Flutie hasn't given them
much of a choice.
	   Actually, the 5-foot-10 (1.75-meter) former Canadian Football
League star has forced Buffalo coach Wade Phillips to make a
difficult decision _ Rob Johnson or Flutie.
	   Flutie has led the Bills to comeback wins in successive weeks.
First it was Indianapolis. Then he ended Jacksonville's unbeaten
hopes Sunday on a 1-yard touchdown run with 13 seconds left.
	   Will Phillips choose the dlrs 25 million franchise quarterback
or the minimum-salary fan favorite who disappeared north of the
border for the past eight years?
	   In all likelihood, it will be back to the sidelines for Flutie.
But maybe not just yet.
	   For the first time all season, Phillips even ducked the question
of who would be the starter when Johnson is healthy.
	   ``We have one quarterback that's hurt and one that's healthy,
and I don't want to get into what-if's,'' Phillips said. ``If Rob's
not able to practice like last week, then Doug will play.''
	   Even though Phillips won't publicly say it, players will.
	   ``Rob's the starting quarterback and we're just very fortunate
Doug's able to come in and do what he did,'' said Bills fullback
Sam Gash.
	   ``Rob's still the guy,'' said Bills running back Thurman Thomas.
``If I was the owner and paid him dlrs 25 million, he's still going
to be the No. 1 guy. We're just happy to have two quality QB's on
the team.''
	   The decision was made when the Bills dealt a first-round pick
for Johnson this past offseason and gave him the most lucrative
signing bonus in team history. The 35-year-old Flutie, told he'd
have a chance to compete for the starting job, never got the
chance.
	   Health permitting, Johnson's the starter.
	   But Johnson's well-being, or lack thereof, has enabled Flutie to
have nearly as much playing time this season.
	   Johnson, 25, has made it through just three of five games this
season and sat out Sunday's 17-16 upset win over Jacksonville with
a rib injury.
	   ``I think it should be Flutie,'' said former Giants quarterback
Phil Simms, now a TV commentator for CBS. ``I like Rob Johnson a
lot, but the team has won two in a row with Flutie and you let it
go until it runs out.''
	   Johnson said his ribs are still bothering him and isn't certain
whether he'll be able to play this Sunday night at Carolina.
	   If Flutie is overlooked in favor of the 6-foot-4 (1.9-meter)
Johnson, it wouldn't be the first time.
	   The former Heisman Trophy winner was drafted in the 11th round
by the Rams in 1985, but elected to sign with the New Jersey
Generals of the USFL. The Rams traded his rights to Chicago the
following season and Flutie played five games with Mike Ditka's
Bears before being dealt to New England for an eighth-round pick.
</TEXT>
