<HEADLINE>
Tennis Glance
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QL; 
 &UR; By BOB GREENE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 
 &UR; STARS &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   _ Pete Sampras won the CA Trophy tournament in Vienna, Austria,
defeating Karol Kucera 6-3, 7-6 (7-3), 6-1.
	   _ Marcelo Rios downed Mark Woodforde 6-4, 6-2 to win the
Heineken Open in Singapore.
	   _ Lindsay Davenport successfully defended her European
Championships title by beating Venus Williams 7-5, 6-3 at Zurich,
Switzerland.
	   _ John McEnroe stopped Henri Leconte 6-4, 6-2 to capture the
Harvey Norman Champions in Sydney, Australia.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; SPEAKING &QC; 
	   ``Once you get to No. 1, it's nice to win and keep playing as
well as you did to get there. You can't help but want to remain
there _ maybe even end the year in No. 1.'' _ Lindsay Davenport.
	   ``I was No. 1, then I went to No. 3, and now I'm coming back,''
_ Marcelo Rios, on winning in Singapore, his seventh title of the
year.
	   ``I hit that ball perfectly. It was great timing and
technique.'' _ Venus Williams, after hammering a 127 mph serve,
women's record, in her European Championships match against Mary
Pierce.
	   ``It was a house of pain.'' _ Nicolas Kiefer, describing his
1{-hour ordeal at the hairdressers where he dyed his hair blond.
	   ``The reason why Pete (Sampras) is No. 1 is because he plays
well on all three surfaces. He's going to be very tough to catch.''
_ Patrick Rafter, after losing in the CA Trophy, an indoor
tournament which Sampras eventually won.
	   ``It's exactly what people want, but then they get mad at me.
That was nothing compared to what I am capable of.'' _ John
McEnroe, after arguing with the umpire and shouting at his opponent
in a senior tournament match in Sydney, Australia.
	   ``There should be some rules. The referees deserve some
respect.'' _ Henri Leconte, saying the senior tour needs to
introduce rules to combat bad behavior.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; SWIFT SERVE &QC; 
	   Venus Williams unleashed the fastest serve ever recorded in
women's tennis during the European Championships when she drilled
an ace clocked at 127.4 mph (205 kph) past a stunned Mary Pierce.
Williams broke her own record _ a blistering 125 mph (201 kph)
serve she delivered at Wimbledon this year.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; SCUD'S RETURN &QC; 
	   Mark Philippoussis has ended his feud with John Newcombe and
Tony Roche and rejoined the Australian Davis Cup team. Ironically,
his first match back will be against Zimbabwe next April. With
Philippoussis, known as Scud because of his powerful serve, sitting
in the stands after refusing to play Davis Cup, Australia was upset
by Zimbabwe in this year's competition.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; SWISS STREAK &QC; 
	   When Lindsay Davenport successfully defended her European
Championships by beating Venus Williams in Zurich, she extended her
five-year winning streak in Switzerland to 17 matches. She has not
lost a set in the past two years in the Zurich tournament. And it
was her sixth tournament title of the year, tops on the Corel WTA
Tour.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; SINGAPORE SNACK &QC; 
	   Australian teen-ager Lleyton Hewitt had breakfast with the
orangutans at the Singapore Zoological Gardens while playing in the
Heineken Open. No one, though, told him how big orangutans grow.
Hewitt wondered whether it was a good idea when he spotted the huge
male orangutans. Fortunately, breakfast turned out to be feeding a
fruit platter to the mother and baby.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; STAUDER SUCCESSOR? &QC; 
	   Klaus Stauder has denied reports that Boris Becker might succeed
him as president of the German Tennis Federation (DTB). Becker, who
is semi-retired and playing only certain tournaments, is the
manager of Germany's Davis Cup team. Speculation that the
three-time Wimbledon champion might succeed Stauder increased when
the DTB president, whose term ends in February 1999, said he would
not stand for reelection. Stauder said Becker ``would no longer
feel free and independent'' if he became DTB president.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; STEFANKI TO COACH &QC; 
	   Sweden's Jonas Bjorkman has taken on Larry Stefanki as his new
coach _ at least for four weeks. If things work out well, they will
sign a one-year contract. The Swede has been without a coach since
he parted company with Swede Fredrik Rosengren earlier this season.
Stefanki coached Chile's Marcelo Rios to No. 1 in the world before
the two parted ways about six weeks before the U.S. Open this year.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; SITES TO SURF &QC; 
	   Moscow: www.kremlin-cup.ru/
	   Stuttgart: www.eurocard-open.de/
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; Tournaments this week &QC; 
 &UR; ATP Tour &QC; 
	   dlrs 975,000 IPB Czech Indoor, carpet, Ostrava, Czech Republic
	   dlrs 725,000 Grand Prix de Lyon, carpet, Lyon, France
 &UR; Corel WTA Tour &QC; 
	   dlrs 926,250 Ladies Kremlin Cup, carpet, Moscow
 &UR; Senior Tour &QC; 
 &UR; Oct. 21-25 &QC; 
	   Harvey Norman Champions, Melbourne, Australia
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; Tournaments week of Oct. 26 &QC; 
 &UR; ATP Tour &QC; 
	   dlrs 2,200,000 Eurocard Open, carpet, Stuttgart, Germany
	   dlrs 315,000 Abierto Mexicano de Tenis, clay, Mexico City
 &UR; Corel WTA Tour &QC; 
	   dlrs 164,250 Bell Challenge, hard, Quebec, Canada
	   dlrs 164,250 Seat Open, carpet, Luxembourg
 &UR; Senior tour &QC; 
 &UR; Oct. 30-Nov. 1 &QC; 
	   dlrs 150,000 NTT Data Champions, Tokyo, Japan
</TEXT>
