<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Caribbean Red Stripe, 1st Ld-Writethru,0458 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Guyana beats Leewards in Red Stripe Bowl final
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Guyana victory, details &QL; 
 &UR; By HOWARD CAMPBELL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   OCHO RIOS, Jamaica (AP) _ Penetrative spin bowling carried
Guyana to an emphatic 52-run victory over the Leeward Islands
Monday in the final of the Red Stripe Bowl one-day cricket
tournament at Kaiser Sports Club.
	   Replying to Guyana's 226 for seven made in 50 overs, the
Leewards tumbled from 78 for one to be bowled out for 174 in 45.5
overs. It was sweet revenge for Guyana, which lost in the 1997
final to the Leewards.
	   Apart from fast bowler Reon King, who picked up the first wicket
off captain Stuart Williams for three in the third over, Guyana's
spinners shared the remaining wickets.
	   None of the Leewards batsmen looked at ease, with Lennox Cush
leading the way with four wickets for 37 runs. Neil McGarrel and
captain Carl Hooper had two wickets each.
	   Opening batsman Wilden Cornwall, the Leewards' most consistent
batsman throughout the tournament, was again among the runs with
45. Runako Morton, with whom he shared a second wicket stand of 77
runs, topscored with 48.
	   But once both were out, wickets fell regularly as Guyana's slow
bowlers took control.
	   Earlier Monday, Guyana's batting struggled after winning the
toss and taking first strike. Openers Clayton Lambert and Andrew
Gonsalves posted 108 for the first wicket in aggressive fashion.
	   Lambert was the dominant partner, slamming 65 off 72 deliveries
in an innings that included one six and seven boundaries. Gonsalves
was run out, making 41 with six boundaries.
	   The remaining Guyanese batsmen failed to capitalize on the good
start. Though sharing a third wicket stand of 41, star batsmen
Hooper (25) and Shivnarine Chanderpaul (29) never looked
threatening as the Leewards fought their way back into contention
through superb fielding and good bowling.
	   Leading the Leewards attack was offspinner Anthony Lake who
captured two wickets for 42 runs.
	   The Leewards had reached the final after appealing the Jamaica
Cricket Board's decision that Trinidad and Tobago should have
contested the match.
	   Trinidad and Tobago were declared winners after Saturday's
semi-final against the Leewards was halted midway the Trinidadians'
innings. Match referee Hugh Perry ruled that Trinidad and Tobago
were winners due to a superior run rate.
	   But the Leewards' management charged that Perry used the wrong
formula to determine the run rate. Their appeal was upheld late
Sunday despite much confusion and controversy. Trinidad and Tobago
reportedly were considering legal action.
</TEXT>
