<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0672 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   JESSE, Nigeria (AP) _ With dozens of charred bodies littering
the town, authorities began burying at least 500 people on Monday,
victims of a devastating pipeline explosion over the weekend. Some
who were too burned to be identified would be placed in mass
graves, officials said. Although flames from the ruptured gasoline
pipeline occasionally flared up to 20 meters (65 feet) in the air,
by late Monday firefighters had stopped fighting the blaze and said
they would wait for it to burn out. Meanwhile relatives converged
on the disaster scene in Jesse, 300 kilometers (180 miles)
southeast of Lagos, to search for remains of their loved ones.
(NIGERIA-OIL EXPLOSION)
	   BEERSHEBA, Israel (AP) _ A Palestinian man threw two hand
grenades near a bus stop crowded with Israeli soldiers on Monday
morning, injuring at least 64 people during a critical point in a
Mideast peace summit in Maryland. In response to the attack, Israel
suspended talks with the Palestinians on all matters unrelated to
security issues and Israel's prime minister said he would not
remain at the talks for an ``unlimited period of time. Three
victims of the attack were in serious condition after the rush hour
assault in the desert town of Beersheba 50 miles (83 kilometers)
south of Jerusalem, and many soldiers were among the wounded.
(ISRAEL-EXPLOSIONS)
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ A Spanish judge on Monday moved closer to
having former Chilean dictator Augusto Pinochet extradited from
Britain to Spain on charges of genocide, torture and terrorism.
Judge Baltasar Garzon, whose arrest order Friday prompted British
police to detain the aging Pinochet in London, added in a second
document sent to Britain specific charges related to 94 alleged
victims of Pinochet's regime, most of them Chileans. The original
order said Pinochet, who is in London recovering from back surgery,
was responsible for the death of Spaniards and others. But it had
cited only one specific case, the kidnapping and disappearance of a
Chilean dissident. Any request for his extradition must be approved
first by Spain's National Court and then by the cabinet of Prime
Minister Jose Maria Aznar before being presented to British
authorities, who would have the final word. (SPAIN-PINOCHET)
	   ROME (AP) _ President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro on Monday formally
asked former Communist Massimo D'Alema to form Italy's 56th
government since World War II. Scalfaro's request came after
D'Alema reported to the president that he has assembled a
parliamentary majority in days of hard bargaining with centrist and
leftists parties. D'Alema is expected to announce his Cabinet
choices Tuesday or Wednesday and go to Parliament for the vote of
confidence that would make him premier in time to attend the
European Union Summit on Friday and Saturday. One of D'Alema's
first appearances as premier-designate will be to join Scalfaro in
meeting with Pope John Paul II Tuesday at the presidential palace.
(ITALY-POLITCS)
	   KAFR EL-DAWAR, Egypt (AP) _ The Egyptian government suspended
five top railway officials Monday after a train jumped its rails
and slammed into a crowded town square, killing 47 people.
Transportation Minister Suleiman Metwally ordered the suspension of
the officials, including the national head of railways and the
managers in the province where the accident occurred, pending an
investigation into the accident. The train flew off the rails as it
pulled into a siding in the station of Kafr el-Dawar town, 30
kilometers (20 miles) southeast of the port city of Alexandria. It
crashed through a barricade and into the town square, killing 47
and injuring 104 people, police officials said. They dismissed
earlier reports of as many as 52 dead, saying that in some cases,
bodies were cut in two and counted twice in preliminary death
tolls. (EGYPT-TRAIN CRASH)
</TEXT>
