<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP Top Financial News,0794 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 0000 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Stocks rose for a fourth straight session
Monday, with a sudden flurry of mergers adding to the optimism
created by last week's cut in Federal Reserve interest rates. The
Dow Jones industrial average rose 49.62 points _ or by 0.6 percent
_ at 8,466.45 after retreating from a 98-point gain that put the
blue-chip barometer above 8,500 for the first time since before the
late August selloff. (US-CLOSING STOCKS)
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ U.S Trade Representative Charlene
Barshefsky on Monday urged the European Union to make more import
efforts to help Asian countries overcome the global crisis, but
faced countercharges the EU was doing more than the United States.
Barshefsky, on a visit to the 15-nation EU, said the economic
crisis had made it critical that the EU and the United States help
other countries ``whose recovery depends in some parts on them
being able to export.'' Barshefsky said Monday that the European
Union should share more of the burden of accepting steel imports.
The European Union said instead it its steel imports had increased
much more than those of the United States. (EU-US-TRADE)
	   DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) _ Dubai on Monday threatened
retaliatory action against the European Union over what it sees as
an unfair and discriminatory duty on Dubai's aluminum exports. ``If
they don't open the door for us, we will do everything legally
possible,'' Mohammed Alabbar, director general of Dubai's
Department of Economic Development, told a press conference. His
warning came ahead of next week's crucial talks on the dispute at a
Gulf Cooperation Council-EU ministerial meeting in Luxembourg. At
the center of the row is a 6 percent EU tax on premium aluminum
exported to Europe by Dubai Aluminum Company and Aluminum Bahrain
in the nearby state of Bahrain, also a member of the GCC.
(EMIRATES-EUROPE)
	   ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) _ Switzerland's UBS AG has lost some
130,000 clients since the announcement last December of the merger
that formed the banking giant, a spokesman said Monday. The loss,
which amounts to around 2 1/2 percent of the bank's total
customers, was lower than expected, UBS spokesman Michael Willi
said. UBS was formed in June as a result of the merger of two major
Swiss banks, Union Bank of Switzerland and Swiss Bank Corp. The
bank had expected to lose between 3 and 4 percent of its customers,
Willi said. (SWITZERLAND-UBS)
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ Government lawyers Monday used videotape
excerpts from pretrial interviews with Microsoft's billionaire
chairman, Bill Gates, to try to show he was behind a controversial
1995 meeting with a rival company to divide the market for Internet
software. Although Gates, the world's wealthiest man, wasn't in the
crowded Washington courtroom, his presence was felt when he
appeared on a large projection screen and on smaller television
sets around the room. What happened during the June 1995 meeting
with executives from rival Netscape Communications Corp. is of
crucial importance to the government, which is trying to show that
Microsoft illegally misused its influence as the maker of the
dominant Windows operating system. (US-MICROSOFT)
	   CHICAGO (AP) _ McDonald's Corp. reported Monday its
third-quarter profits rose 7 percent, matching Wall Street
expectations, as the company showed solid sales increases in the
United States and abroad despite a global economic crisis. For the
three months ended Sept. 30, the world's largest fast-food chain
reported net income of dlrs 482.2 million, or 69 cents a diluted
share, compared to dlrs 448.9 million, or 63 cents a diluted share,
the same period a year ago. Sales rose 5 percent to dlrs 9.25
billion from dlrs 8.8 billion. (US-EARNS-MCDONALD'S)
	   LONDON (AP) _ The fabled Madame Tussaud's wax museum, London's
top tourist attraction, has been sold, its parent company announced
Monday. Pearson PLC said it has sold The Tussauds Group, a British
leisure business made up of a number of theme parks and the popular
museum, to Charterhouse Development Capital of London for 352
million pounds (dlrs 598.4 million). Pearson, which also owns the
London-based business newspaper the Financial Times and the French
business daily Les Echos, said proceeds from the sale of The
Tussauds Group would be used to cut debt. The company already has
said it intends to sell an indirect 4.3 percent stake in British
Sky Broadcasting, currently worth around 350 million pounds (dlrs
595 million). (BRITAIN-MADAME TUSSAUD'S)
</TEXT>
