<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-People and Places,0871 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
People and places in the news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Gloria Estefan, Geri Halliwell, Elton John,
Prince Charles, Queen Fabiola of Belgium, careful Arab drivers and
Yasser Arafat. Some items may have moved as separates. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Gloria Estefan will join Meryl Streep in ``50
Violins'' in her first feature-film role.
	   The Cuban-born singer will play Streep's friend and co-worker in
the movie about a woman who taught youngsters in East Harlem how to
play the violin, Miramax Films said Monday.
	   Streep took over the lead, Roberta Tzavaras, from Madonna, who
spent three months learning violin but dropped out before filming
began due to creative differences with director Wes Craven.
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Geri Halliwell will soon fill her
post-Spice days with the duties of a goodwill ambassador.
	   Halliwell, a.k.a. Ginger Spice, will promote awareness of
reproduction health issues in Britain for the U.N. Population Fund.
	   ``She will be a great ambassador for young people,'' Fund
spokesman Alex Marshall said Monday.
	   Halliwell, 26, quit the all-girl British pop group May 31,
citing ``differences between us,'' and recently signed a new record
deal.
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
	   ATLANTA (AP) _ Georgia has been good to Elton John.
	   ``People always ask me, 'Why do you have a place in Atlanta?'
It's because people here have always been that nice to me,'' said
John, who also owns homes in England and France. ``I've always been
welcomed. I feel at home.''
	   So much at home that he persuaded Disney Chairman Michael Eisner
to pick Atlanta's Alliance Theater for the premiere of Disney's
first original for-the-stage musical. John and lyricist Tim Rice
composed the music for ``Elaborate Lives: The Legend of Aida,''
which is playing in Atlanta through Nov. 8.
	   ``It gives the show a sense of continuity,'' John said. ``'Aida'
was conceived in Hollywood but written in Atlanta. Time Rice even
wrote a lot of his stuff in Atlanta as well.''
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
	   LONDON (AP) _ The longtime paramours toured a succession of
Aegean islands on a borrowed yacht, sat side-by-side on the deck
painting watercolors and simply relaxed in the sunshine.
	   All in all, it sounds a luxurious but hardly groundbreaking week
away _ except the pair in question were Prince Charles and Camilla
Parker Bowles and the leisurely cruise marked their first vacation
as a couple, several newspapers reported Monday.
	   A spokeswoman for Charles, the son of Queen Elizabeth II,
declined any comment on the reports that he and Mrs. Parker Bowles
recently spent a week island-hopping with two other couples.
	   Charles and Mrs. Parker Bowles, who is divorced, have spent time
together abroad before, but always traveled separately and met up
as part of a large group, the newspapers reported.
	   The Daily Mail quoted one ``senior royal official, not usually
given to sentimentality'' as saying: ``They looked so sweet
together, it brought tears to my eyes.''
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Queen Fabiola of Belgium saw
contrasting sides of Thai society Monday, visiting two
disadvantaged groups during the day and dining with the Thai royal
family in the evening.
	   The queen's visit as the guest of King Bhumibol Adulyadej and
Queen Sirikit began Saturday. On Sunday, she attended church at
Assumption University in Bangkok, an institution affiliated with
the Roman Catholic Church.
	   On Monday, Fabiola toured a royal rehabilitation project for
blind women at Nakorn Pathom, 50 kilometers (30 miles) west of the
capital. The project trains the women in making arts and
handicrafts.
	   She also visited a hospital for handicapped children.
	   Before attending a dinner given by King Bhumibol, she watched
traditional drama and dance performances as well as an elephant
show at a cultural center outside of Bangkok.
	   The queen was to leave Tuesday for Malaysia.
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
	   DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) _ For one week this month, this
oil-rich emirate will be using a carrot instead of a stick to
convince car drivers to be on their best behavior.
	   During a weeklong campaign starting Saturday, traffic police
will cite 12 motorists a day for following safe driving rules,
radio and press reports said Monday.
	   The safe drivers _ or RoadStars _ will share a total of 100,000
dirhams (dlrs 27,400) in prize money, the report said.
	   During the campaign, police will be on the lookout for drivers
who wear seat belts, drive within speed limits, use their turn
signals and display courteous behavior, the Gulf News reported.
	   Traffic accidents are the number one cause of death in this
country of 2.4 million.
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Taking a break from grueling Mideast talks,
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat hopped on a bicycle and rode
around sprawling Wye Plantation in Maryland for 90 minutes.
	   The 68-year-old Arafat has been dogged by persistent rumors of
failing health because of his trembling lower lip and hands, but
has dismissed the speculation as subversive propaganda.
	   The Al Ayyam daily, which is close to the Palestinian Authority,
reported Monday that ``Arafat rode the bicycle well and did not
show signs of fatigue.'' 	   
</TEXT>
