<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar lower, Tokyo stock prices rise in early trading
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar edged lower against the yen early
Tuesday in lackluster trading, while Japanese stock prices moved
moderately higher after an overnight rise on Wall Street.
	   The dollar bought 114.62 yen in early trading, down 0.10 yen
from late Monday in Tokyo but above its New York level of 114.28
yen late Monday.
	   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 85.80
points, or 0.63 percent, to 13,653.00 points in the first 30
minutes of trading. On Monday, the Nikkei closed up 286.66 points,
or 2.16 percent.
	   In currency dealings, the dollar was higher against the Japanese
currency from its late New York level, as the dollar's strength
against the German mark led Japanese short-term players to buy back
the U.S. currency against the yen.
	   The dollar continued to benefit from speculation that the
Bundesbank, Germany's central bank, may lower interest rates at its
policy-setting meeting on Thursday, traders said.
	   But they said the dollar's direction against the yen remains
unclear.
	   On the stock market, an overnight gain on Wall Street encouraged
investors in Tokyo. The Dow rose 49.62 points _ or 0.6 percent _ to
finish Monday's session at 8,466.45.
	   Trading remained moderate in Tokyo, however, as many investors
took a wait-and-see attitude on expectations the government will
consider stimulus steps to lift Japan's moribund economy, dealers
said.
	   Kaoru Yosano, head of the Ministry of International Trade and
Industry, told reporters Monday that the government may come up
with a new set of economic stimulus measures next month.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was up 7.36 points, or 0.72 percent, to 1,030.28
points. The TOPIX closed up 16.24 points, or 1.61 percent, the day
before.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese
government bond rose to 0.835 percent from Monday's finish of 0.815
percent, driving its price down to 108.62 yen from 108.82 yen.
 &UR; (km-dj)
</TEXT>
