<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo,0646 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
West concerned about latest Kosovo skirmishes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Recaps previous. &QL; 
 &UR; By GEORGE JAHN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Western powers are voicing concern
about increased violence in Kosovo that has taken place despite a
political agreement intended to stop the fighting. But the prospect
of NATO airstrikes to end the bloodshed remains on hold.
	   NATO commander Wesley Clark planned to visit Belgrade on Tuesday
to discuss how far Yugoslav authorities still have to go in pulling
out army units from Kosovo, under an agreement signed with U.S.
negotiator Richard Holbrooke on avoiding NATO intervention.
	   The visit was set amid increased signs of battle preparedness in
parts of Kosovo, a predominantly ethnic Albanian province of
Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant republic.
	   More Yugoslav army troops were positioned southwest of Pristina,
the Kosovo capital, after a surge of weekend violence that left
three Serb policemen dead and led to mutual accusations between
authorities and radical Albanians on who started the bloodshed.
	   Western officials, concerned about odan Milosevic. The agreement headed off NATO
airstrikes against Serb forces for the time being, disappointing
ethnic Albanians who want outright independence.
	   Rubin said U.S. mediator Christopher Hill was telling Kosovo
Liberation Army guerrillas they should not try to provoke Serb
forces into taking actions that would heighten the possibility of
airstrikes against them.
	   It would be a mistake, Rubin said, for the rebel group ``to
consider NATO its air force. That will not be tolerated by the
U.S.''
	   He said Yugoslav compliance with commitments to disarm in Kosovo
has been mixed. Over the past month, he said, about half of the
Yugoslav Army units that had moved into Kosovo earlier this year
have left the province.
	   Hundreds of people have been killed this year in Milosevic's
crackdown on separatists, and hundreds of thousands more have fled
their homes to escape the violence.
	   In Paris, NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said Monday the
recent upsurge in violence doesn't undermine the accord on Kosovo.
	   ``I think there are provocateurs and provocations, but we must
continue to hold the line'' and carry out the accord, Solana said.
	   Milosevic has until Oct. 27 to reduce the level of Yugoslav army
and Serb police forces in Kosovo or face airstrikes by the Atlantic
alliance.
	   Solana avoided comment on how pressure could be placed on the
Kosovo Albanians not to attack the Serb forces.
	   In Kosovo, reports of shelling and shooting, along with a
Yugoslav army deployment along a key road, caused the U.N. refugee
agency to call off two convoys of relief supplies on Monday.
	   The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees planned to send out the
two convoys on Tuesday along with two others already scheduled.
	   The troops who moved out of Pristina to the southwest on Sunday
are normally stationed in the capital, and therefore could remain
in the province under the withdrawal plan.
	   Serb officials on Monday again blamed the violence on the KLA,
saying the guerrillas want to provoke a fight that would jeopardize
the agreement and bring NATO intervention.
	   A 2,000-member international verification force is being
organized by the 54-nation Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe to ensure that Yugoslavia honors its
promises. About 25 members of an advance team for the monitors are
in Kosovo.
</TEXT>
