<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Student Strike,0488 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Security tight as students plan new mass demonstrations
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: Will be led after Paris march begins at 0800 GMT. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos staffing &QL; 
 &UR; By DEBORAH SEWARD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Thousands of French police were placed on maximum
alert Tuesday to prevent disturbances by high school students
planning to hold their second major nationwide protest in less than
a week.
	   Hundreds of thousands of high school students were expected to
demonstrate across the country to press their demands for more
teachers, better equipment and buildings and a lighter course load.
	   The French government has promised to provide more money soon,
but it has no quick remedy for the ailing education system or for
high youth unemployment _ a deep fear for many French teen-agers.
	   The biggest demonstration Tuesday was expected in Paris, where
at least 4,000 police were mobilized to contain any outbreaks of
violence.
	   The Socialist-led government, wary of the political damage done
by university student protests 30 years ago, appears to be taking
no chances in letting Tuesday's demonstrations get out of control.
	   Police planned to monitor the Paris demonstration on television
monitors in the basement of their headquarters in hopes of
identifying hooligans. Extra police were to be deployed in suburban
trains leading to Paris.
	   Adult monitors wearing white helmets also were to march
alongside the students to help maintain calm.
	   Last Thursday's student protests in a number of cities were
badly marred by violence, some of it instigated by rowdy youths
bent on disrupting the demonstrations.
	   Some 150 people were arrested nationwide. In Paris, five people
were injured, 50 shops were looted and more 100 cars were damaged,
some of them burned.
	   In Normandy, the police chief advised merchants to take
precautions Tuesday to protect store windows against possible
damage in case of rioting.
	   Students in the capital planned to march from the Place d'Italie
in southeastern Paris toward the National Assembly, where lawmakers
were to debate the new budget.
	   Education Minister Claude Allegre and Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin, a former Education Minister, have promised to come up with
funds to prevent the crisis from deepening.
	   Six weeks after the school year has begun, some students are
still without teachers. Many schools, especially in disadvantaged
working-class neighborhoods, are badly in need of modernization.
	   Polls show that the students have widespread public support, and
Jospin's popularity has dipped in the past week as the high school
protests swelled.
	   The students have expressed disappointment in Allegre, and many
do not believe he will be able to keep his promises.
	   The student protests have won some sympathy among their
teachers. At least two teachers' unions called on their members to
join Tuesday's march.
</TEXT>
