<SLUG> BC-Spain-Castro visit,0269 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fidel Castro receives warm welcome on visit to southern Spanish
</HEADLINE>
town of Merida &QL; 
 &UR; By MAR ROMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MERIDA, Spain, (AP) _ Cuban leader Fidel Castro received a warm
welcome when he arrived for a brief visit to the southern Spanish
town of Merida.
	   Speaking to reporters a few hours after his arrival on Monday he
thanked people for an ``extraordinary'' welcome and praised
relations between Spain and Cuba.
	   ``The relationship is going fine, it has improved a lot,''
Castro said, adding that this was especially pleasing because this
year marks Cuba's 100 years of independence from Spain, its former
colonial master.
	   After his arrival, Castro met Juan Carlos Rodriguez Ibarra,
president of Extremadura, the region where Merida is situated.
	   Later some 800 people gathered outside the regional government
offices where the two met and shouted ``Cuba yes, embargo no,''
referring to the United States' decades-old embargo on Cuba.
	   Castro, 72, came to Merida, a city of 65,000 people some 217
miles (350 kilometers) south west of Madrid after attending the
Ibero-American summit in the Portuguese city of Oporto last
weekend.
	   On Tuesday he was to visit some Roman ruins, meet Spanish
President Jose Maria Aznar in Madrid and later return to Cuba.
	   Castro was invited to Extremadura by Rodriguez Ibarra, who
visited him in Havana in July.
	   As she waited to see him, housewife and grandmother Juana
Barrera said she was nervous and excited. ``He has been a leader
for a long time, so I don't think he is such a bad man,'' she said.
</TEXT>
