<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Palestinian-Prisoners,0661 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fate of thousands of Palestinian prisoners to be determined in Wye
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SAMAR ASSAD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TURMOUS AYYA, West Bank (AP) _ Saieda Hamzeh remembers gently
caressing the young face of her 16-year-old son Muntasir. Three
years later, a full-grown beard now covers that face and barbed
wire keeps a mother's touch away.
	   Muntasir is serving a five-year sentence in Israel's Megiddo
prison for possessing and preparing to use explosives. The
possibility of Muntasir's early release, and that of some 3,000
other Palestinians in Israeli jails, is one of the issues at the
summit between Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in the United States.
	   For Arafat, the issue is critical. The Palestinian leader,
already under pressure from opponents who claim he has conceded too
much to Israel, needs to bring back something solid to his people
from the talks.
	   For Netanyahu, prisoner release is one of the more difficult
concessions. The prime minister was highly critical of his
predecessors for releasing prisoners and has accused Arafat of a
``revolving-door'' policy regarding militants in Palestinian
custody.
	   In Jerusalem, Israeli police spokeswoman Linda Menuhin said
Monday that police submitted a list of 100 Palestinian prisoners to
the Israeli delegation at Wye Plantation, outside Washington, D.C.,
but would not say if some or all would be released.
	   Her boss, Public Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani told Israel
radio that up to 100 prisoners, primarily those who are sick or
jailed for non-violent crimes, could be released soon.
	   But Arafat will need to hold out for a more significant offer
than that to satisfy his public.
	   ``Arafat feels the pressure, the street reminds him every day of
the importance of the prisoners,'' Mrs. Hamzeh said.
	   Hundreds of Palestinians marched in the Gaza Strip on Monday to
demand the release of relatives held in Israeli jails.
	   Holding pictures of husbands, fathers and sons, an estimated 700
Palestinian women and children demanded that the Palestinian
delegation to the Mideast summit secure the release of prisoners
held for security offenses.
	   ``Our people cannot accept any agreement without the release of
all the prisoners,'' said Sufian Abu Zaida, an official in the
Palestinian Authority.
	   Such protests have been a daily occurrence in
Palestinian-controlled cities, even before the start of the summit,
giving Arafat something to point to as he argues the issue.
	   Though clearly skeptical, the 49-year-old Hamzeh said she is
hopeful that her son, now 19, will be released once a deal is
reached.
	   ``He has only two years left, Israel usually releases those who
have a short time left,'' Hamzeh, wearing a tradional full-length
embroidered dress, said with a warm smile.
	   Because the explosives her son prepared were never used in an
attack and he did not cause the death of anyone, he could be among
those released.
	   But for her next door neighbor, Summana Jabara _ whose father is
serving a life sentence for planting a bomb in a Jerusalem market
23 years ago that killed and injured tens of Israelis _ the chances
of greeting a jailed relative are slim.
	   Israel has said it would never release Palestinians who have
``blood on their hands.''
	   ``People like my father, no one even mentions them any more,''
said Jabara, who was three months old when her father Ahmed was
arrested. ``I have no hopes that he will be released.''
	   Mrs. Hamzeh said she has plans for her son and will hold him to
a promise he made to get his high school diploma and enroll in
college.
	   She also said that if her son is released, she'll make sure he
stays out of trouble.
	   ``Before he was arrested he would get frustrated and stomp out
of the house when I asked him what he was doing or where he was
going,'' Mrs. Hamzeh said. ``Now, he won't get away with that.'' 	   
</TEXT>
