<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-Germany,0347 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kohl to pay Poland farewell visit and receive award
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Lead expected after 1230 GMT award ceremony. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ The outgoing German Chancellor Helmut
Kohl, a strong supporter of Poland's integration with the western
security and economic structures, is heading to Warsaw to say
farewell.
	   An invitation from Poland's President Aleksander Kwasniewski,
made after Kohl lost his re-election bid last month, is to
recognize Kohl's efforts to lead the former Warsaw Pact country and
a former foe, into the family of western nations.
	   During Tuesday's one-day visit, Kohl, who steps down Oct. 27,
was to receive from Kwasniewski Poland's highest distinction, the
White Eagle Order. He was also to meet with Prime Minister Jerzy
Buzek.
	   Buzek has invited Chancellor-elect Gerhard Schroeder, who is to
be sworn in on Oct. 27, to visit Poland in early November,
government spokesman Jaroslaw Sellin said.
	   Ever since the two neighboring nations, with a long history of
warfare, signed the landmark friendship treaty in 1991 aimed at
burying the ghosts of World War II, Kohl has supported efforts to
mend relations.
	   Even in his campaign this year, Kohl advocated closer ties with
Poland, saying postwar Germany's success at converting its western
neighbor France from historic foe to close ally can and should be
repeated across the eastern border.
	   ``The way to mutual understanding is often hard,'' Kohl said a
year ago. ``It means overcoming some prejudices. But our experience
with France shows that `good neighborliness' can succeed if many
people on both sides take it to heart.''
	   Championed by Germany, Poland was among the first former Warsaw
Pact countries invited to join NATO and is on the short list for
early EU entry as well.
	   Germany is also the biggest market for Polish exports.
	   Relations are sometimes strained, though, by calls from
conservatives within Kohl's camp for Poland to do more to address
demands from Germans forced out of Poland after World War II for
compensation for their land. 	   
</TEXT>
