<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-World Series-Yankees,0401 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Torre with one decision left for Game 3
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By TOM WITHERS &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN DIEGO (AP) _ Relaxed and seemingly rested after a long early
morning flight, the Yankees enjoyed a few laughs around the batting
cage Monday at Qualcomm Stadium.
	   Most of the fun came at the expense of New York's pitchers, who
got in a few meek hacks in preparation for Tuesday night's Game 3
of the World Series when the American League champions will have to
play some National League ball.
	   David Wells took a Ruthian swing that produced a high popup,
Jeff Nelson's bunt attempt plopped in the netting above his head,
and Hideki Irabu looked like he was holding a bat for the first
time.
	   ``Oh, this is ugly,'' one Yankee said while watching the
pitchers take their rips.
	   It's easy to have fun in California, especially when you're two
wins away from a World Series title.
	   Little has gone wrong for the Yankees so far. They're finally
hitting, everyone's healthy and only a total collapse seems to
stand in their way from finishing their dream season on top.
	   Still, manager Joe Torre has some concerns and at least one
problem to resolve.
	   A former manager in the National League, Torre knows the
subtleties of that league's game will force him to be on top of his
game Tuesday night.
	   ``This is the National League now, and you have to pay a lot
more attention when you manage,'' he said before the Yankees'
workout. ``You've got to be aware of double switches.''
	   Torre has already decided to make a switch in his starting
lineup for Game 3. What that switch is, he's still not certain.
	   Rookie Ricky Ledee, who has gone 4-for-6 in the first two games
of the Series and who reached base in his first seven at-bats, will
not start in left field for Game 3 against San Diego left-hander
Sterling Hitchcock.
	   Torre will chose from among Tim Raines _ a switch-hitter _ or
right-handers Chili Davis and rookie Shane Spencer to start in
left.
	   ``I don't know yet,'' Torre said. ``It's not going to be Ledee
so take that and run with it. But I haven't really zeroed in on
anybody. ... You've got a few candidates, and the wild card guy
could be Chili Davis because he threw his hat in the ring last
night (1-for-3, one RBI, two walks). But I'm going to give it a
little more thought.''
</TEXT>
