<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Latin American Briefs,0719 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dominican Republic. Some items may have moved as separates.
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items from Peru, Cuba, Mexico, Ecuador and the
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LIMA, Peru (AP) _ A judge has blocked an attempt to close
discotheques that restrict entry based on race, stripping the
government's consumer rights group of its ability to punish racist
businesses.
	   The group, Indecopi, had fined and ordered four exclusive Lima
discotheques temporarily closed after an investigation showed they
denied entry to people with Indian features or dark skin.
	   The owner of one discotheque appealed the ruling, arguing that
Indecopi did not have the jurisdiction to order business closed for
racism. That authority belonged only to the courts, the owner said.
	   Members of Peru's Indian majority are regularly barred from
entering from Lima's exclusive restaurants and clubs, which cater
to a white or mixed race elite. People with the Andean features of
Peru's mountainous interior are most frequently discriminated
against.
	   ___
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ A U.S. animal-rights group has carried its
campaign for vegetarianism to a place where many people in recent
years already _ unwillingly _ have abandoned meat: Cuba.
	   People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals sent a Sept. 22
letter to President Fidel Castro urging him to give up meat as an
example. A copy of the letter was faxed Monday to The Associated
Press.
	   ``Adopt a vegetarian diet. Such a decision would make a powerful
statement of solidarity with both the exploited animals and people
forced to desensitize themselves in low-paid slaughterhouse jobs,''
it said.
	   But lack of meat is one of the most common complaints of Cubans
struggling with economic hardships caused by the collapse of
socialist trading partners.
	   While traditional Cuban cuisine is heavy on pork, beef and
chicken, many Cubans rarely find more than a pound of chicken _ if
that _ in their monthly rations.
	   Bruce G. Friedrich, coordinator of PETA's vegetarian campaign,
said the Virginia-based group is still waiting for a response from
Castro.
	   ___
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Government officials took a stronger stand
Monday against U.S. plans to put a nuclear waste site near its
border with Mexico.
	   Cabinet members who earlier had waffled on steps to oppose the
dump are now promising strong action against the projected
low-level radioactive waste dump in Sierra Blanca, Texas, about 15
miles from the Mexican border.
	   Energy Secretary Luis Tellez, who previously had said the waste
dump did not pose a danger to Mexican border residents, said he
shared his government's concern over its location.
	   The Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission, appointed by
Gov. George W. Bush, is to meet Oct. 22 to decide whether to
license the dump.
	   ___
	   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) _ President Jamil Mahuad's approval rating
has fallen sharply since he took office more than two months ago,
mainly due to unpopular austerity measures that have caused prices
to soar, a poll showed Monday.
	   A poll by the private company Market showed that 35 percent of
Ecuadoreans approved of his presidency, down 30 percentage points
from results of a poll taken shortly after Mahuad entered office
Aug. 10.
	   In a national strike called by Ecuador's unions on Oct. 1 to
protest the measures, three people died in clashes between police
and protesters.
	   The reforms have increased the price of fuel by as much as 400
percent and sent the cost of many basic foods and public
transportation skyrocketing.
	   Pollsters surveyed 1,600 people across Ecuador on Oct. 3-4. The
margin for error was plus or minus 3 percentage points.
	   ___
	   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) _ An American tourist and
three Dominicans drowned in flooding this weekend in the Dominican
Republic, police said Monday.
	   The deaths were in Jarabacoa, an area north of Santo Domingo
that is popular with campers and hikers. Two of the dead were
identified as Ramon Alcantara Cabrera, 48, and American tourist
Bryan Cluso, 54. Police did not know Cluso's hometown, and they had
not identified the two other victims.
	   Police said Cluso was believed to have died when a small boat he
was in capsized on the Yague del Norte River. Alcantara died when a
bridge he was on was swept away.
</TEXT>
