</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Peru-Racism,0244 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Peru judge backs racist dance clubs
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LIMA, Peru (AP) _ A judge has blocked an attempt to close
discotheques that restrict entry based on race, stripping the
government's consumer rights group of its ability to punish racist
businesses.
	   Peru's consumer rights watchdog Indecopi had fined and ordered
four exclusive Lima discotheques temporarily closed after an
investigation showed they denied entry to people with Indian
features or dark skin.
	   The owner of one discotheque appealed the ruling, arguing that
Indecopi did not have the legal power to order business closed for
racism, which can only be done by the courts.
	   The judge backed the appeal, ordering Indecopi to stop further
investigations.
	   The court ruling left Indecopi powerless to investigate or
punish racist businesses, consumer groups charge.
	   ``This questionable decision will promote discrimination in our
country. It is impossible to understand how the judicial system
could back these racist practices,'' the vice president of Peru's
Association of Consumers and Users, Herley Llerena, said Monday.
	   Members of Peru's Indian majority are regularly barred from
entering from Lima's exclusive restaurants and clubs, which cater
to a white or mixed race elite. People with the Andean features of
Peru's mountainous interior are most frequently discriminated
against.
	   Indecopi had acted after receiving many complaints about the
four clubs.
</TEXT>
