r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-China-Vietnam     10-19 0331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Vietnam </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chinese, Vietnamese leaders discuss border dispute in Beijing
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ China and Vietnam are making progress in settling
their border disputes and have replaced former enmity with smooth
bilateral ties, Premier Zhu Rongji said in talks with Vietnamese
Prime Minister Phan Van Khai.
	   Khai was to meet on Tuesday with President Jiang Zemin.
	   In the talks on Monday, Zhu said it is in both countries'
interests to settle the land border and sea boundary in the Beibu
Gulf by 2000, a time frame set by the ruling communist parties of
China and Vietnam, the state-run Xinhua News Agency reported late
Monday night.
	   Khai said Vietnam also was determined to settle the boundary
soon, Xinhua reported.
	   The two also discussed ways to promote trade and investment,
Xinhua said without giving details. Senior economic officials were
accompanying the two premiers in the talks.
	   Afterward, Chinese and Vietnamese officials signed a treaty on
judicial assistance in civil and criminal cases, a border trade
agreement and a consular treaty. Xinhua gave no details, but
problems between the two countries include smuggling and poor
quality goods.
	   Trade along the border has boomed since the two former enemies
mended ties and normalized relations in 1991. Trade grew from dlrs
30 million in 1991 to dlrs 1.44 billion last year, according to
Vietnamese statistics reported in the newspaper Investment in
Vietnam.
	   In 1979, China attacked Vietnam to punish Hanoi for invading
Cambodia 10 days earlier.
	   During the 1980s, relations between the two countries remained
chilly. This was the first time a Vietnamese prime minister has
lead a delegation on a visit to China since normalization.
	   Khai planned to tour southern China before returning to Hanoi on
Friday.
	   China has 41 investment projects in Vietnam with total
investment capital of dlrs 102 million, while Hong Kong has 191
projects capitalized at dlrs 2.5 billion. 	   
</TEXT>
