<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Explosion,0707 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Charred bodies litter the ground after Nigerian pipeline blast
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS pvs &QL; 
 &UR; AP Graphic NIGERIA EXPLOSION
 &UR; By FRANK AIGBOGUN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JESSE, Nigeria (AP) _ Drawn by rumors that a huge pool of
gasoline was free for the taking, hundreds of people converged on
this small Nigerian town over the weekend.
	   On Monday, though, it was their relatives who converged here,
searching out the charred remains of their brothers, sisters,
fathers and mothers, killed as the fountain of fuel burst into a
fireball.
	   ``It is finished,'' cried Charity Unurhoro, after finding the
horribly burned bodies of her mother and brother, who she could
identify only by his necklace. ``Now everything is over for me.''
	   As she cried, a man quietly told a young relative to fetch a
wheelbarrow. It was time to take the corpse of the boy and his
mother home.
	   For dozens of families, Monday's search ended the same way.
	   ``I cannot take him,'' said James Daniel, after finding the body
of his brother, Joseph. ``Let the government bury him.''
	   The fire, which began Saturday as gasoline spilled from a
pipeline, killed at least 500 people and left at least 100
hospitalized, military officials said.
	   The area's hospitals _ most of which only have a handful of
doctors and nurses and little in the way of burn care _ were
overwhelmed by the disaster. Doctors were overworked and medicine
in short supply, local officials said.
	   With dozens of charred, unidentified bodies littering the town
and flames still occasionally flaring up to 20 meters (65 feet)
high, authorities began the grim task Monday of burying the dead.
	   By Monday night, firefighters had stopped battling the flames
and waited for the blaze, which spread thick black smoke for miles
(kilometers), to burn itself out.
	   A mass grave was being dug at the edge of the town to bury
hundreds of unidentified corpses, many burned beyond recognition.
Separate burials were held Monday for at least 52 of the dead, and
dozens of people took corpses back to surrounding villages.
	   Military ruler Gen. Abdulsalami Abubakar flew in by helicopter
for a 15-minute visit. He said the government would pay for medical
treatment, but that there would be no compensation to survivors,
apparently because many of those killed were believed to be
scavenging fuel.
	   But area residents were furious over the deaths.
	   ``This is a tragedy of huge proportions,'' the Rev. Andrew
Imadu, a local minister, said at one funeral in Jesse. ``Our own
people have been driven by deprivation to such a desperate search
for livelihood.''
	   Southeastern Nigeria, while rich in oil, is scarred by decades
of poverty and villagers in some areas are believed to regularly
sabotage oil pipelines in order to file claims for compensation.
	   The above-ground pipeline links a refinery in the southeastern
city of Warri, 350 kilometers (210 miles) southeast of Lagos, with
the northern city of Kaduna, nearly 600 kilometers (380 miles)
away.
	   Over the weekend, hundreds of people descended on the town as
rumors spread that a huge pool of gasoline _ which had spilled from
the pipeline into a concrete well _ was available for the taking,
according to J.I. Ogude, village chief of Jesse.
	   The scavenging had been going on since at least Saturday
morning, he said, adding that people gathering at the scene were
taking the fuel to sell on the black market.
	   An official for Nigeria's state petroleum corporation, speaking
on condition of anonymity, said authorities believed the pipeline
had purposely been punctured, and that scavengers tools had sparked
the explosion. Some newspaper reports, though, said a cigarette may
have started the conflagration.
	   Some corpses _ including those of some children _ were found
still clutching plastic cups, funnels and cans to collect the fuel.
	   The charred body of one woman was found with her dead baby still
strapped to her back. Many other victims were villagers sleeping in
their homes.
	   Despite Nigeria's enormous oil wealth, years of government
misrule and corruption have resulted in almost perpetual fuel
shortages, skyrocketing black-market prices and long gasoline
lines. 	   
</TEXT>
