<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Colombia-Pipeline Attack,0696 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Death toll mounts, guerrilla role probed in pipeline explosion
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos planned &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS and UPDATES with quote from former foreign minister &QL; 
 &UR; By JARED KOTLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) _ An apparent sabotage attack on an oil
pipeline continued to claim lives Monday and authorities sought to
determine whether leftist rebels were indeed responsible for the
blast, which unleashed a fireball that killed at least 47 people.
	   The usually outgoing rebels have been silent, fueling suspicion
they were behind the early-morning explosion and fire Sunday in the
village of Machuca, in the northwestern state of Antioquia.
	   At least 60 people were badly burned when flames consumed the
rural hamlet. Two of the burn victims _ a 60-year-old man and a
7-year-old boy _ died Monday, the governor's office in Medellin
reported.
	   Authorities appeared to rule out an accident. Government
officials and representatives of the company that operates the
Ocensa pipeline stopped short of accusing the guerrillas, but
expressed indignation.
	   ``We are truly perplexed and indignant,'' said Nestor Humberto
Martinez, the interior minister. ``If it is proven that insurgents
committed this ferocious and barbaric act they owe a clear
explanation to the nation.''
	   The rebel National Liberation Army, or ELN, was suspected in the
blast but had no public comment. Antonio Picon, a civilian member
of a Medellin peace committee, told The Associated Press that
jailed ELN spokesman Francisco Galan said the rebels would make a
statement Tuesday.
	   ``They are carrying out an investigation and tomorrow morning
they will produce a statement saying either 'it was us' or 'it
wasn't,'' said Picon.
	   Colombia's second-largest rebel group, the ELN is active in the
area of Sunday's blast and routinely dynamites pipelines, accusing
the government of selling out to foreign oil companies.
	   Oil company officials said they found a 1.5-meter (4-foot) deep
by 2-meter (6-foot) wide crater in the ground where the pipeline
was ruptured.
	   ``The conclusion is that criminal hands were at work, that it
was an attack,'' said Jorge Suarez, support manager for the
pipeline, which is jointly owned by the state oil company,
Ecopetrol, and a foreign consortium including British Petroleum,
U.S.-based Triton Energy Ltd., Total S.A. of France and two
Canadian companies.
	   Suarez said the crater was ``typical of an explosives attack.''
	   Guerrilla groups often target Colombia's Cano Limon pipeline,
which has been bombed repeatedly this year. But Sunday's explosion
was only the third Ocensa bombing since the pipeline began
operating in November 1995. The 510-mile (820-kilometer) pipeline
carries 350,000 barrels of crude daily from eastern Colombia to the
Caribbean.
	   If the rebels are found responsible, it could poison the
atmosphere for peace talks to put an end to Colombia's 34-year
civil war. President Andres Pastrana is set to begin negotiations
Nov. 7 with the country's other leading guerrilla faction, the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia. In February, preliminary
peace talks are scheduled to get under way with the ELN.
	   Civilian leaders were giddy last week after a mountain meeting
with ELN leaders to set the talks' agenda. But the mood soured
after Sunday's tragedy.
	   ``I hope the ELN wasn't responsible, but if it was it owes some
explanations, because this goes against everything we've been
talking about,'' said former foreign minister Augusto Ramirez
Ocampo, one of the civilians leading the peace contacts with the
rebels.
	   The pre-dawn blaze scorched wooden homes where villagers were
sleeping and most of the victims were children. One survivor
described a 150 foot (50 meter) ball of flame roaring along a river
before bowling into Machuca.
	   ``We heard people screaming. When we turned around to look
everything was on fire,'' survivor Lacides Atehortua told the
Medellin newspaper El Colombiano.
	   Oil company officials said as many as 30,000 barrels of crude
were spilled and that they expected to have the pipeline repaired
and back in operation on Tuesday. 	   
</TEXT>
