u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Malaysia-Politics     10-19 0387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Government appeals for end to street protests
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Malaysia's Home Ministry has
appealed to citizens to use the ballot box and not street protests
to bring about political change, a newspaper reported Tuesday.
	   Deputy Home Minister Tajol Rosli Ghazali said Malaysians
disenchanted with Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, Asia's
longest-serving ruler, should wait until the general election to
express their frustrations.
	   ``We cannot topple a government which has been elected by the
people,'' Tajol Rosli was quoted as saying by the New Straits Times
daily.
	   In recent weeks, protests have flared throughout the Southeast
Asian nation in support of jailed dissident Anwar Ibrahim. Mahathir
fired him on Sept. 2 as deputy premier and finance minister. Anwar
was subsequently arrested for launching a campaign urging political
reform.
	   If the governing United Malays National Organization party wants
to change its leader, it too must use an election, Tajol Rosli
reportedly said.
	   ``If we don't like Dr. Mahathir Mohamad, we have to topple him
through UMNO elections and we have to oust UMNO through general
elections,'' he was quoted as saying. An UMNO internal election is
scheduled for next year and a general vote in 2000.
	   Demonstrations held in the capital and in dozens of towns have
demanded Anwar's release, and the ouster of Mahathir, who has ruled
Malaysia for 17 years.
	   On Monday, several thousand protesters gathered near the rural
village of Sementa in the surrounding state of Selangor in defiance
of a blanket police ban on political rallies.
	   Several activists from various political parties spoke before
police arrived an hour later to break up the gathering,
eye-witnesses said.
	   Public gatherings of more than three or four people are deemed
illegal in Malaysia.
	   During Saturday's street protest in front of the National
Palace, police arrested around 140 people, including 17 women, who
called for Malaysia's constitutional monarch to rescue the
country's rapidly declining political climate.
	   A police spokesman was quoted as saying in Tuesday's Star daily
that 133 protesters remain under detention. Several dozen people
have been taken to hospital after complaining of police brutality.
</TEXT>
