</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Liquidity Crunch </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai government wants state banks to increase lending
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ With Thai commercial banks reluctant to
make loans, the Council of Economic Ministers wants state-run banks
to start lending more money as a means of reviving economic growth,
a government spokesman said on Tuesday.
	   Thailand's economic crisis has had a devastating effect on the
country's banking system. As businesses fail or hit hard times,
they have been unable to repay loans to commercial banks.
	   Non-performing loans have been estimated as high as 40 percent
of commercial banks' loan portfolios. Consequently, they have been
refusing to extend credit even to healthy companies, leaving them
unable to purchase raw materials.
	   Government spokesman Akaphol Sorasuchart said state-run banks
such as the Bank of Agriculture and Agricultural Cooperatives, the
Government Savings Bank, the Government Housing Bank and the Export
and Import Bank of Thailand would be asked to extend more loans.
	   Priority should be given to housing loans for low-income
earners, and to businesses involved in exporting and agriculture,
Akaphol said.
	   He added that more money for loans from state institutions could
come from an anticipated aid package Japan is expected to extend to
Southeast Asian nations, including Thailand.
</TEXT>
